WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:02.000
[Unknown]: I.V.M.

00:00:31.000 --> 00:00:35.000
[Amit Varma]: The Economist magazine coined this phrase in 1977 in the context of the Netherlands,

00:00:35.000 --> 00:00:40.000
[Amit Varma]: which had a stroke of good fortune when natural gas was discovered in Groningen in 1959.

00:00:40.000 --> 00:00:42.000
[Amit Varma]: Or was it really good fortune?

00:00:42.000 --> 00:00:48.000
[Amit Varma]: Because of this natural resource, foreign exchange flooded into the country and their own currency became stronger.

00:00:48.000 --> 00:00:53.000
[Amit Varma]: This meant imports became cheaper and people could now afford the best goods from across the world.

00:00:53.000 --> 00:00:57.000
[Amit Varma]: As a result of this, the local manufacturing sector went into decline.

00:00:57.000 --> 00:01:03.000
[Amit Varma]: What initially seemed like good luck, later appeared to be not quite so lucky after all.

00:01:03.000 --> 00:01:06.000
[Amit Varma]: A classic modern case of the Dutch disease is Venezuela.

00:01:06.000 --> 00:01:10.000
[Amit Varma]: Large reserves of oil were discovered there more than a century ago in 1914,

00:01:10.000 --> 00:01:17.000
[Amit Varma]: and a relatively poor country, suddenly sitting on humongous oil reserves, became quite rich as the years went by.

00:01:17.000 --> 00:01:22.000
[Amit Varma]: But what this also did was that it lowered the incentives for the governments that ran the country

00:01:22.000 --> 00:01:26.000
[Amit Varma]: to learn the good habits that take a nation towards prosperity.

00:01:26.000 --> 00:01:31.000
[Amit Varma]: There was so much oil wealth that governments quickly developed patterns of patronage and cronyism.

00:01:31.000 --> 00:01:36.000
[Amit Varma]: Bad governance and poor economic policies did not have the cost they should have

00:01:36.000 --> 00:01:39.000
[Amit Varma]: because there was always so much oil wealth floating around.

00:01:39.000 --> 00:01:43.000
[Amit Varma]: In a situation like this, sooner or later, something always has to give.

00:01:43.000 --> 00:01:47.000
[Amit Varma]: Venezuela is now going through an enormous humanitarian crisis,

00:01:47.000 --> 00:01:51.000
[Amit Varma]: caused by bad economics but enabled by the bonanza of oil.

00:01:51.000 --> 00:01:55.000
[Amit Varma]: I'll explore some of that in this episode, but before I do, here's a thought.

00:01:55.000 --> 00:02:00.000
[Amit Varma]: Does the same process by which too much of a good thing can be bad for countries,

00:02:00.000 --> 00:02:02.000
[Amit Varma]: can it also be bad for individuals?

00:02:15.000 --> 00:02:16.000
[Unknown]: Welcome to the Seen and the Unseen.

00:02:16.000 --> 00:02:21.000
[Amit Varma]: The 19th century Venezuelan hero Simon Bolivar once said,

00:02:21.000 --> 00:02:26.000
[Amit Varma]: to understand revolutions and their participants, we must observe them at close range

00:02:26.000 --> 00:02:28.000
[Amit Varma]: and judge them at great distance.

00:02:28.000 --> 00:02:29.000
[Amit Varma]: Stop quote.

00:02:29.000 --> 00:02:34.000
[Amit Varma]: My guest today is Alexandra Ulmer, who spent a few years studying Venezuela at close range,

00:02:34.000 --> 00:02:38.000
[Amit Varma]: as an oil correspondent for Reuters based in Caracas, the capital of Venezuela,

00:02:38.000 --> 00:02:42.000
[Amit Varma]: but is now based in Bombay, at some distance from Venezuela.

00:02:42.000 --> 00:02:46.000
[Amit Varma]: I asked her to join me on the show to chat not just about Venezuela,

00:02:46.000 --> 00:02:53.000
[Amit Varma]: but also the craft of news reporting, as the title of this episode, Reporting Venezuela, indicates.

