00:04:08.000 --> 00:04:10.000
[Amit Varma]: Welcome to the scene in The Unseen, Alexandra.

00:04:10.000 --> 00:04:12.000
[Guest]: Thank you, Amit. Such a treat to be here.

00:04:12.000 --> 00:04:15.000
[Amit Varma]: So tell me about how you became a journalist.

00:04:15.000 --> 00:04:17.000
[Amit Varma]: What drew you towards journalism?

00:04:17.000 --> 00:04:21.000
[Guest]: I had always had two twin passions, one of them was current affairs,

00:04:21.000 --> 00:04:23.000
[Guest]: and the other one was writing.

00:04:23.000 --> 00:04:25.000
[Guest]: And for some strange reason, I never really thought to put them together

00:04:25.000 --> 00:04:29.000
[Guest]: until I was at university and I started working on this school paper.

00:04:29.000 --> 00:04:32.000
[Guest]: And I remember not being able to sleep the night before my first article,

00:04:32.000 --> 00:04:34.000
[Guest]: which was something very mundane and uninteresting, came out.

00:04:34.000 --> 00:04:36.000
[Guest]: And that's when I knew I was hooked.

00:04:36.000 --> 00:04:38.000
[Amit Varma]: So where did you go from there?

00:04:38.000 --> 00:04:42.000
[Guest]: I started as an intern with Reuters in Buenos Aires.

00:04:42.000 --> 00:04:46.000
[Guest]: I was fascinated with Latin America and wanted to get going there.

00:04:46.000 --> 00:04:49.000
[Guest]: Then went on to be a stringer for Reuters again in Chile,

00:04:49.000 --> 00:04:51.000
[Guest]: just on the other side of the Andes,

00:04:51.000 --> 00:04:54.000
[Guest]: where I did a lot of reporting on economics and mining

00:04:54.000 --> 00:04:57.000
[Guest]: and learned a lot more about how the world goes around,

00:04:57.000 --> 00:05:00.000
[Guest]: but was frankly a little bored as a journalist.

00:05:00.000 --> 00:05:05.000
[Guest]: And then Venezuela came to the fore, and about four years ago I moved to Caracas.

00:05:05.000 --> 00:05:07.000
[Amit Varma]: And what's a food chain of journalism like?

00:05:07.000 --> 00:05:10.000
[Amit Varma]: Like you begin as an intern, then you're a stringer,

00:05:10.000 --> 00:05:11.000
[Amit Varma]: then you're a full-fledged reporter.

00:05:11.000 --> 00:05:13.000
[Amit Varma]: How does the job description change?

00:05:13.000 --> 00:05:15.000
[Amit Varma]: What are the kind of things that you did on the job?

00:05:15.000 --> 00:05:19.000
[Guest]: So as an intern in Buenos Aires, I had the best of all worlds.

00:05:19.000 --> 00:05:24.000
[Guest]: I was able to cover fun but also fundamental events

00:05:24.000 --> 00:05:27.000
[Guest]: like the legalization of gay marriage in Argentina,

00:05:27.000 --> 00:05:30.000
[Guest]: and I wrote soft features on being a vegetarian in Buenos Aires,

00:05:30.000 --> 00:05:32.000
[Guest]: the meat capital of the world.

00:05:32.000 --> 00:05:33.000
[Amit Varma]: You're a vegetarian?

00:05:33.000 --> 00:05:34.000
[Amit Varma]: Yes, I am.

00:05:34.000 --> 00:05:35.000
[Guest]: Horror.

00:05:35.000 --> 00:05:38.000
[Guest]: I've never been as happy as I am in India.

00:05:38.000 --> 00:05:39.000
[Amit Varma]: Welcome to Mumbai!

00:05:39.000 --> 00:05:40.000
[Amit Varma]: Yes, thank you.

00:05:40.000 --> 00:05:44.000
[Guest]: It's very refreshing after the barbecues of Latin America.

00:05:44.000 --> 00:05:47.000
[Amit Varma]: I'd trade places with you any day.

00:05:47.000 --> 00:05:52.000
[Guest]: Yeah, well, then if you're a meat lover, Argentina is the place.

00:05:52.000 --> 00:05:56.000
[Guest]: And, you know, as you go up the food chain as a stringer,

00:05:56.000 --> 00:06:01.000
[Guest]: I had a lot of responsibilities for somewhat mindless tasks

00:06:01.000 --> 00:06:04.000
[Unknown]: like at the time covering the local stock market,

00:06:04.000 --> 00:06:07.000
[Guest]: running out to press conferences, learning the ropes,

00:06:07.000 --> 00:06:11.000
[Guest]: which is essential and is what you build on to become a better journalist.

00:06:11.000 --> 00:06:15.000
[Amit Varma]: And what are the sort of values that you picked up in,

00:06:15.000 --> 00:06:18.000
[Amit Varma]: which you pick up in any good news organization,

00:06:18.000 --> 00:06:20.000
[Amit Varma]: you know, like Reuters obviously is,

00:06:20.000 --> 00:06:22.000
[Amit Varma]: in terms of the kind of journalism you do?

00:06:22.000 --> 00:06:24.000
[Amit Varma]: What's the rigor that you have to follow?

00:06:24.000 --> 00:06:26.000
[Guest]: It's incredibly rigorous.

00:06:26.000 --> 00:06:29.000
[Guest]: It's a fantastic school of journalism.

00:06:29.000 --> 00:06:31.000
[Guest]: It's daunting because you're learning on the spot,

00:06:31.000 --> 00:06:34.000
[Guest]: and journalism in that sense is much more of a craft

00:06:34.000 --> 00:06:38.000
[Guest]: than something you learn within an established school or institution.

00:06:38.000 --> 00:06:41.000
[Guest]: So you learn to be rigorous with your facts.

00:06:41.000 --> 00:06:43.000
[Guest]: You learn to check with sources.

00:06:43.000 --> 00:06:45.000
[Guest]: You learn to question everything.

00:06:45.000 --> 00:06:47.000
[Guest]: You learn to be fair.

00:06:47.000 --> 00:06:49.000
[Guest]: Of course, all these issues are deeply philosophical,

00:06:49.000 --> 00:06:53.000
[Guest]: and we can debate them at great length because there's no perfect recipe for it.

00:06:53.000 --> 00:06:57.000
[Guest]: But especially, I think, as a foreign news outlet in countries

00:06:57.000 --> 00:06:59.000
[Guest]: where sometimes the local media is coward

00:06:59.000 --> 00:07:03.000
[Guest]: or doesn't have the resources to cover something as well as it would have otherwise,

00:07:03.000 --> 00:07:05.000
[Guest]: you become a frame of reference.

00:07:05.000 --> 00:07:10.000
[Guest]: So there's great responsibility on having smart, articulate, fair coverage.

00:07:10.000 --> 00:07:14.000
[Amit Varma]: And, you know, one of the very clear demarcations in foreign media

00:07:14.000 --> 00:07:17.000
[Amit Varma]: is the line between news and opinion,

00:07:17.000 --> 00:07:20.000
[Amit Varma]: which sometimes gets muddy in India.

00:07:20.000 --> 00:07:22.000
[Amit Varma]: And you were, of course, a reporter all along.

00:07:22.000 --> 00:07:26.000
[Amit Varma]: So, you know, how do you sort of get to that level of objectivity

00:07:26.000 --> 00:07:29.000
[Amit Varma]: where you sort of keep your feelings about what you're reporting

00:07:29.000 --> 00:07:31.000
[Amit Varma]: out of your reportage itself?

00:07:31.000 --> 00:07:33.000
[Amit Varma]: Like, do you have to make a special effort to do that?

00:07:33.000 --> 00:07:35.000
[Amit Varma]: Can you go too far?

00:07:35.000 --> 00:07:37.000
[Guest]: I think you always have to be careful.

00:07:37.000 --> 00:07:40.000
[Guest]: I think in some ways it's easier when you're not reporting on your own country

00:07:40.000 --> 00:07:43.000
[Guest]: because you're more detached from the situation.

00:07:43.000 --> 00:07:48.000
[Guest]: But, you know, being fair also entails portraying the situation accurately.

00:07:48.000 --> 00:07:50.000
[Guest]: Like one of the old adages in journalism is

00:07:50.000 --> 00:07:52.000
[Guest]: if one person says it's raining outside,

00:07:52.000 --> 00:07:55.000
[Guest]: the other person says it's, you know, a beautiful, glorious day

00:07:55.000 --> 00:07:58.000
[Guest]: and you should go to the beach, your job isn't to portray both sides.

00:07:58.000 --> 00:08:01.000
[Guest]: Your job is to open the curtains and tell readers what's going on.

00:08:01.000 --> 00:08:03.000
[Guest]: Now, that's a clean-cut example.

00:08:03.000 --> 00:08:05.000
[Guest]: In the real world, it can get muddier than that.

00:08:05.000 --> 00:08:09.000
[Guest]: But I think trying to find the sweet spot between being fair

00:08:09.000 --> 00:08:11.000
[Guest]: to the different sides and ideas involved,

00:08:11.000 --> 00:08:16.000
[Guest]: but also, you know, not just being a robot who's throwing out the facts

00:08:16.000 --> 00:08:19.000
[Guest]: coming from different sides and actually assessing how the situation is evolved,

00:08:19.000 --> 00:08:23.000
[Guest]: how politicians or whoever's claims stake up to what they've actually done

00:08:23.000 --> 00:08:26.000
[Guest]: is in essence an essential part of our job.

00:08:26.000 --> 00:08:29.000
[Amit Varma]: And in a sense, like you said, the example you gave is clear-cut.

00:08:29.000 --> 00:08:32.000
[Amit Varma]: When it comes to something like covering a country like Venezuela, for example,

00:08:32.000 --> 00:08:35.000
[Amit Varma]: where the economics is very complicated,

00:08:35.000 --> 00:08:38.000
[Amit Varma]: the politics is very complicated, society is complicated,

00:08:38.000 --> 00:08:43.000
[Amit Varma]: then does it involve a case of just having to learn a lot of things

00:08:43.000 --> 00:08:46.000
[Amit Varma]: before you can even begin to report?

00:08:46.000 --> 00:08:47.000
[Guest]: I think so.

00:08:47.000 --> 00:08:51.000
[Guest]: But I think in a place like Venezuela, which essentially has become devoid of fact,

00:08:51.000 --> 00:08:52.000
[Guest]: it's very difficult to do that.

00:08:52.000 --> 00:08:54.000
[Guest]: I'll give you an example.

00:08:54.000 --> 00:08:56.000
[Guest]: Venezuela has rampant corruption.

00:08:56.000 --> 00:09:00.000
[Guest]: We know that is one of the fundamental reasons this government has been so inept

00:09:00.000 --> 00:09:03.000
[Guest]: and has basically left Venezuela penniless.

00:09:03.000 --> 00:09:06.000
[Guest]: For a long time, it was very difficult for us to say that.

00:09:06.000 --> 00:09:09.000
[Guest]: We knew money was disappearing, but if you don't have the proof,

00:09:09.000 --> 00:09:11.000
[Guest]: you don't write it if you're a rigorous journalist.

00:09:11.000 --> 00:09:15.000
[Guest]: Of course, now there are multiple cases across the United States and in Europe

00:09:15.000 --> 00:09:17.000
[Guest]: where, you know, a single businessman has been accused

00:09:17.000 --> 00:09:20.000
[Guest]: and has pleaded guilty to embezzling, say, a billion dollars.

00:09:20.000 --> 00:09:25.000
[Guest]: That gives you an idea of the scale of graft we're talking about.

00:09:25.000 --> 00:09:28.000
[Guest]: But for a long time, it can be frustrating because to be a rigorous reporter,

00:09:28.000 --> 00:09:30.000
[Guest]: you can't just throw around baseless claims,

00:09:30.000 --> 00:09:32.000
[Guest]: but that also means you're missing a fundamental part of the story

00:09:32.000 --> 00:09:34.000
[Guest]: that you're struggling to tell the readers,

00:09:34.000 --> 00:09:37.000
[Guest]: and I think that's the deepest frustration there can be.

00:09:37.000 --> 00:09:40.000
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, because there must be times when you absolutely know something,

00:09:40.000 --> 00:09:44.000
[Amit Varma]: but you cannot say it, and you have to kind of get there from other places.

00:09:44.000 --> 00:09:47.000
[Amit Varma]: So before you went to Venezuela, did you want to go to Venezuela,

00:09:47.000 --> 00:09:49.000
[Amit Varma]: or was it something that Reuters offered you the opportunity,

00:09:49.000 --> 00:09:52.000
[Amit Varma]: and then you looked into it and said, huh, that's interesting?

00:09:52.000 --> 00:09:56.000
[Guest]: No, I had been fascinated by Venezuela, mesmerized for a long time.

00:09:56.000 --> 00:09:58.000
[Guest]: I had gotten a student grant when I was at university

00:09:58.000 --> 00:10:01.000
[Guest]: to do a project on political street art there,

00:10:01.000 --> 00:10:05.000
[Guest]: as one does when one is a bright-eyed, bushy-tailed university student.

00:10:05.000 --> 00:10:07.000
[Guest]: And I had spent two weeks in the country

00:10:07.000 --> 00:10:10.000
[Guest]: and had been reading obsessively ever since,

00:10:10.000 --> 00:10:12.000
[Guest]: but I was very deterred by the security situation there

00:10:12.000 --> 00:10:14.000
[Guest]: and never thought I could actually live there

00:10:14.000 --> 00:10:16.000
[Amit Varma]: because it was too dangerous and scared me.

00:10:16.000 --> 00:10:17.000
[Amit Varma]: Which year was this?

00:10:17.000 --> 00:10:20.000
[Amit Varma]: I went there as a student in 2011.

00:10:20.000 --> 00:10:24.000
[Guest]: And moved there in 2014 after going for a brief stint

00:10:24.000 --> 00:10:29.000
[Guest]: and seeing that I could live there, you know, despite the crime concerns.

00:10:29.000 --> 00:10:35.000
[Amit Varma]: So when you started reporting in Venezuela, how easy was access?

00:10:35.000 --> 00:10:39.000
[Guest]: Well, access on the street to people was wonderfully easy.

00:10:39.000 --> 00:10:43.000
[Guest]: I mean, Venezuelans are expansive, fun, Caribbean people who love to chat.

00:10:43.000 --> 00:10:46.000
[Guest]: So after Chile, which is a much kind of more dour, closed society,

00:10:46.000 --> 00:10:48.000
[Guest]: it was a treat for me to just go out

00:10:48.000 --> 00:10:50.000
[Guest]: and be able to interview people in the supermarket lines

00:10:50.000 --> 00:10:54.000
[Guest]: and have them genuinely tell me about their lives and their sufferings.

00:10:54.000 --> 00:10:56.000
[Guest]: Because they wanted to, they wanted to be heard,

00:10:56.000 --> 00:10:58.000
[Guest]: and that's the way they are.

00:10:58.000 --> 00:11:01.000
[Guest]: Conversely, the government is fairly shut off.

00:11:01.000 --> 00:11:04.000
[Guest]: At the time, we still had the occasional press conference.

00:11:04.000 --> 00:11:06.000
[Guest]: Sometimes they would answer questions,

00:11:06.000 --> 00:11:11.000
[Guest]: but it was the kind of situation where GDP, inflation, crime data,

00:11:11.000 --> 00:11:15.000
[Guest]: emigration data, none of that was being published anymore.

00:11:15.000 --> 00:11:17.000
[Guest]: As you mentioned at the start of the podcast, I covered oil,

00:11:17.000 --> 00:11:21.000
[Guest]: and that meant covering the big, omnipresent state oil company.

00:11:21.000 --> 00:11:23.000
[Guest]: I spent four years in Venezuela,

00:11:23.000 --> 00:11:26.000
[Guest]: and I genuinely don't think they ever answered one of my questions.

00:11:26.000 --> 00:11:28.000
[Guest]: You know, when you're writing a story,

00:11:28.000 --> 00:11:31.000
[Guest]: you send in a request for comment by phone or by email

00:11:31.000 --> 00:11:34.000
[Guest]: to give the person concerned a chance to respond,

00:11:34.000 --> 00:11:37.000
[Guest]: and I never got a single answer to my emails.

00:11:37.000 --> 00:11:40.000
[Guest]: I mean, it's that kind of black hole situation you're talking about.

00:11:40.000 --> 00:11:42.000
[Guest]: So it forces you to be a kind of creative, enterprising reporter

00:11:42.000 --> 00:11:44.000
[Guest]: to get to the stories,

00:11:44.000 --> 00:11:47.000
[Guest]: which always means you're missing a significant chunk of data

00:11:47.000 --> 00:11:48.000
[Guest]: and the government side.

00:11:48.000 --> 00:11:50.000
[Guest]: At the end of the day, it's self-defeating for the government

00:11:50.000 --> 00:11:53.000
[Guest]: because they don't speak out, right?

00:11:53.000 --> 00:11:56.000
[Amit Varma]: Right, and of course, distrust towards the media is an attitude

00:11:56.000 --> 00:12:00.000
[Amit Varma]: that really came out much earlier from the time Chávez took over

00:12:00.000 --> 00:12:02.000
[Amit Varma]: because like a lot of populists,

00:12:02.000 --> 00:12:05.000
[Amit Varma]: he kind of looked at the media as part of the elites

00:12:05.000 --> 00:12:07.000
[Amit Varma]: who were antagonistic to him,

00:12:07.000 --> 00:12:11.000
[Amit Varma]: and he tried to sort of control communications and all of that,

00:12:11.000 --> 00:12:14.000
[Amit Varma]: parallels of which we see in many other countries.

00:12:14.000 --> 00:12:18.000
[Amit Varma]: So tell me a little bit about how Venezuela got here,

00:12:18.000 --> 00:12:21.000
[Amit Varma]: you know, starting from before Maduro,

00:12:21.000 --> 00:12:23.000
[Amit Varma]: like when Maduro was president,

00:12:23.000 --> 00:12:25.000
[Amit Varma]: starting from maybe even before Chávez,

00:12:25.000 --> 00:12:28.000
[Amit Varma]: like a lot of people lay the blame quite correctly

00:12:28.000 --> 00:12:32.000
[Amit Varma]: for what's going on to the bad economic policies in Chávez's time,

00:12:32.000 --> 00:12:34.000
[Amit Varma]: which have continued with Maduro.

00:12:34.000 --> 00:12:39.000
[Amit Varma]: But Venezuela was both oil rich and in deep trouble a lot before that.

00:12:39.000 --> 00:12:42.000
[Guest]: It's been a turbulent history. Tell me a little bit about that.

00:12:42.000 --> 00:12:45.000
[Guest]: Absolutely. I mean, it's been a cycle of booms and busts

00:12:45.000 --> 00:12:48.000
[Guest]: basically due to the oil barrel.

00:12:48.000 --> 00:12:52.000
[Guest]: So Venezuela was, by some metrics,

00:12:52.000 --> 00:12:54.000
[Guest]: one of the richest countries in Latin America

00:12:54.000 --> 00:12:57.000
[Guest]: where this elite, this filthy rich would travel to Miami

00:12:57.000 --> 00:13:00.000
[Guest]: and famously say, give me two of everything, it's so cheap.

00:13:00.000 --> 00:13:04.000
[Guest]: Of course, that fueled a lot of inequality and discontent

00:13:04.000 --> 00:13:06.000
[Guest]: and a sense that the political establishment,

00:13:06.000 --> 00:13:09.000
[Guest]: which was basically two political parties that would rotate power

00:13:09.000 --> 00:13:11.000
[Guest]: through democratic elections,

00:13:11.000 --> 00:13:15.000
[Guest]: but rotate power amongst themselves, wasn't representative.

00:13:15.000 --> 00:13:18.000
[Guest]: And there had been sporadic violence and turbulence

00:13:18.000 --> 00:13:20.000
[Guest]: in the country for a long time.

00:13:20.000 --> 00:13:25.000
[Guest]: And Chávez, who came from a poor family from the Savannah lowlands,

00:13:25.000 --> 00:13:29.000
[Guest]: really spoke to the people who felt marginalized by the system.

00:13:29.000 --> 00:13:31.000
[Guest]: And because Venezuela is an oil rich country,

00:13:31.000 --> 00:13:34.000
[Guest]: there's this idea that we are a rich country.

00:13:34.000 --> 00:13:37.000
[Guest]: We should not be poor. This something has gone wrong

00:13:37.000 --> 00:13:39.000
[Guest]: and someone is to blame for it.

00:13:39.000 --> 00:13:43.000
[Guest]: And Chávez diagnosed that problem brilliantly, as many populists do,

00:13:43.000 --> 00:13:46.000
[Guest]: and was elected in 1998.

00:13:46.000 --> 00:13:49.000
[Guest]: There was immediate virulent opposition to him

00:13:49.000 --> 00:13:52.000
[Guest]: from the elite in media and politics, etc.

00:13:52.000 --> 00:13:56.000
[Guest]: And that culminated in a series of marches in 2002

00:13:56.000 --> 00:13:58.000
[Guest]: that led to a brief coup against him,

00:13:58.000 --> 00:14:00.000
[Guest]: where he was deposed for three days.

00:14:00.000 --> 00:14:04.000
[Guest]: It remains a very complex, fiercely argued about episode

00:14:04.000 --> 00:14:06.000
[Guest]: about exactly what happened to him.

00:14:06.000 --> 00:14:10.000
[Guest]: Ultimately, he was reinstated by military loyalists.

00:14:10.000 --> 00:14:11.000
[Guest]: And after that, some would say,

00:14:11.000 --> 00:14:14.000
[Guest]: he became much more paranoid about any attempts against him

00:14:14.000 --> 00:14:16.000
[Guest]: and clamped down much more on institutions,

00:14:16.000 --> 00:14:19.000
[Guest]: the press, and any opposition he could see.

00:14:19.000 --> 00:14:22.000
[Amit Varma]: In fact, there are memorable reports that during the coup,

00:14:22.000 --> 00:14:25.000
[Amit Varma]: he chatted with a hero of his, Fidel Castro, on the phone.

00:14:25.000 --> 00:14:27.000
[Amit Varma]: And Castro told him that, you know, whatever you do,

00:14:27.000 --> 00:14:29.000
[Amit Varma]: don't surrender.

00:14:29.000 --> 00:14:32.000
[Amit Varma]: And it's interesting to me how, you know, obviously,

00:14:32.000 --> 00:14:35.000
[Amit Varma]: from 1958 to 1998, you had this sort of kleptocracy,

00:14:35.000 --> 00:14:37.000
[Amit Varma]: this oligarchy of these two parties,

00:14:37.000 --> 00:14:40.000
[Amit Varma]: which kind of controlled the economy in the system of patronage,

00:14:40.000 --> 00:14:43.000
[Amit Varma]: where the oil wealth was sort of,

00:14:43.000 --> 00:14:46.000
[Amit Varma]: and which was also incredibly corrupt.

00:14:46.000 --> 00:14:49.000
[Amit Varma]: And Chávez detected that correctly and got to power.

00:14:49.000 --> 00:14:52.000
[Amit Varma]: But what I always find kind of interesting is that

00:14:52.000 --> 00:14:54.000
[Amit Varma]: for the first five or six years of his time,

00:14:54.000 --> 00:14:57.000
[Amit Varma]: he professed himself to be non-ideological,

00:14:57.000 --> 00:14:59.000
[Amit Varma]: where he said, I'm not a communist, I'm not a capitalist,

00:14:59.000 --> 00:15:02.000
[Amit Varma]: even though, I mean, he had communist influences.

00:15:02.000 --> 00:15:06.000
[Amit Varma]: He was a big fan of Marx and various other communist thinkers

00:15:06.000 --> 00:15:08.000
[Amit Varma]: right from his student days.

00:15:08.000 --> 00:15:10.000
[Guest]: But, you know, he said, I believe in the third way,

00:15:10.000 --> 00:15:13.000
[Amit Varma]: which was, you know, perhaps a reference to Tony Blair's third way.

00:15:13.000 --> 00:15:16.000
[Amit Varma]: But after 2002 and then 2004,

00:15:16.000 --> 00:15:19.000
[Amit Varma]: what seemed to happen is that he hardened enormously

00:15:19.000 --> 00:15:21.000
[Amit Varma]: and spoke about 21st century socialism

00:15:21.000 --> 00:15:24.000
[Amit Varma]: and went in all the directions that he went in.

00:15:24.000 --> 00:15:28.000
[Amit Varma]: So do you think that sort of change in direction

00:15:28.000 --> 00:15:31.000
[Amit Varma]: came from political imperatives?

00:15:31.000 --> 00:15:33.000
[Guest]: It's a very interesting question.

00:15:33.000 --> 00:15:36.000
[Guest]: I undoubtedly think that he felt very vulnerable

00:15:36.000 --> 00:15:39.000
[Guest]: after the coup and after being reinstated.

00:15:39.000 --> 00:15:43.000
[Guest]: And his instinct was to try to therefore control whatever he could.

00:15:43.000 --> 00:15:48.000
[Guest]: And the influence of Fidel Castro and other politicians

00:15:48.000 --> 00:15:52.000
[Guest]: led to him pushing for much more control over the economy, especially.

00:15:52.000 --> 00:15:54.000
[Guest]: And he enacted a series of policies

00:15:54.000 --> 00:15:58.000
[Guest]: that would really be the downfall of Venezuela ultimately,

00:15:58.000 --> 00:16:01.000
[Guest]: namely imposing currency controls in 2003,

00:16:01.000 --> 00:16:05.000
[Guest]: which is what led to the mind-boggling distortions

00:16:05.000 --> 00:16:07.000
[Guest]: we see today in Venezuela

00:16:07.000 --> 00:16:10.000
[Guest]: that are to blame for much of the current crisis.

00:16:10.000 --> 00:16:13.000
[Guest]: And yes, I think he's a dominating personality

00:16:13.000 --> 00:16:15.000
[Guest]: and he was a dominating politician.

00:16:15.000 --> 00:16:16.000
[Guest]: He was a dominating president.

00:16:16.000 --> 00:16:19.000
[Guest]: His instinct was to control. Yes.

00:16:19.000 --> 00:16:22.000
[Amit Varma]: And that kind of became worse, A, because he's got Castro advising him

00:16:22.000 --> 00:16:24.000
[Amit Varma]: on one side and on the other side.

00:16:24.000 --> 00:16:26.000
[Amit Varma]: I mean, the reason I sort of thought of that

00:16:26.000 --> 00:16:29.000
[Amit Varma]: was when I was kind of reading through all of this,

00:16:29.000 --> 00:16:34.000
[Amit Varma]: one parallel that came to mind was our own earlier Prime Minister Indira Gandhi

00:16:34.000 --> 00:16:38.000
[Amit Varma]: who, you know, took over the Congress party in the mid-60s,

00:16:38.000 --> 00:16:44.000
[Amit Varma]: but she was fighting against the established order in her own party.

00:16:44.000 --> 00:16:46.000
[Amit Varma]: And to distinguish herself from them,

00:16:46.000 --> 00:16:49.000
[Amit Varma]: she took this populist socialist line and did a lot of things

00:16:49.000 --> 00:16:52.000
[Amit Varma]: which were economically disastrous,

00:16:52.000 --> 00:16:55.000
[Amit Varma]: but which if you understand the political imperatives

00:16:55.000 --> 00:16:57.000
[Amit Varma]: and a need to create a brand for herself

00:16:57.000 --> 00:17:01.000
[Amit Varma]: and distinguish herself from them kind of made sense.

00:17:01.000 --> 00:17:03.000
[Amit Varma]: And, you know, the other part of, I mean,

00:17:03.000 --> 00:17:05.000
[Amit Varma]: a lot about Chavez reminds me of Narendra Modi as well.

00:17:05.000 --> 00:17:08.000
[Amit Varma]: And the other part of his rise to power

00:17:08.000 --> 00:17:11.000
[Amit Varma]: and what happened when he got there was just kind of like

00:17:11.000 --> 00:17:14.000
[Amit Varma]: a dog chasing a car and catching the car and not knowing what to do

00:17:14.000 --> 00:17:17.000
[Amit Varma]: because he was incredibly good at campaigning.

00:17:17.000 --> 00:17:20.000
[Guest]: He had no idea whatsoever of how to govern.

00:17:20.000 --> 00:17:21.000
[Guest]: Interesting analogy.

00:17:21.000 --> 00:17:24.000
[Guest]: Yes, I mean, Chavez at heart was a showman, right?

00:17:24.000 --> 00:17:27.000
[Guest]: And he had the whole country or much of the country behind him.

00:17:27.000 --> 00:17:28.000
[Guest]: The masses loved him.

00:17:28.000 --> 00:17:32.000
[Guest]: It was like religious fervor going to his rallies.

00:17:32.000 --> 00:17:36.000
[Guest]: It was unlike anything anyone had seen before.

00:17:36.000 --> 00:17:42.000
[Guest]: And when you had that kind of unquestioning love,

00:17:42.000 --> 00:17:44.000
[Guest]: his worst instincts were unleashed, right?

00:17:44.000 --> 00:17:46.000
[Guest]: And Venezuela was a democracy,

00:17:46.000 --> 00:17:49.000
[Guest]: but it didn't have entirely solid institutions.

00:17:49.000 --> 00:17:53.000
[Guest]: And when Chavez was in power from 1999 to 2013,

00:17:53.000 --> 00:17:55.000
[Guest]: he had plenty of time to dig away at them.

00:17:55.000 --> 00:17:58.000
[Guest]: But I think, yes, his instinct was always to campaign.

00:17:58.000 --> 00:18:00.000
[Guest]: And he would always boast,

00:18:00.000 --> 00:18:02.000
[Guest]: we've had more elections than anywhere else in the world.

00:18:02.000 --> 00:18:05.000
[Guest]: How can you criticize us for not being a democracy?

00:18:05.000 --> 00:18:06.000
[Guest]: But that's what he reveled in, right?

00:18:06.000 --> 00:18:10.000
[Guest]: And that's what he loved, not the day-to-day nitty gritty.

00:18:10.000 --> 00:18:13.000
[Guest]: And that tendency was exacerbated by the fact that

00:18:13.000 --> 00:18:17.000
[Guest]: during 10 years of his governance, you had an oil bonanza.

00:18:17.000 --> 00:18:19.000
[Guest]: You didn't have to worry about the nitty gritty.

00:18:19.000 --> 00:18:21.000
[Amit Varma]: The oil money was just gushing in.

00:18:21.000 --> 00:18:23.000
[Amit Varma]: And this happened because 9-11 happened,

00:18:23.000 --> 00:18:26.000
[Amit Varma]: and therefore the oil spigot slowed down in the Middle East,

00:18:26.000 --> 00:18:30.000
[Amit Varma]: and Venezuela was certainly much in demand.

00:18:30.000 --> 00:18:33.000
[Amit Varma]: And also he kind of revived the OPEC at this time, right?

00:18:33.000 --> 00:18:35.000
[Guest]: Yes, yes, he was instrumental in that.

00:18:35.000 --> 00:18:39.000
[Guest]: And I think the fact that the oil prices shot up was a saving grace.

00:18:39.000 --> 00:18:41.000
[Guest]: I mean, politics is also about luck,

00:18:41.000 --> 00:18:45.000
[Guest]: and Chávez was an incredibly lucky politician.

00:18:45.000 --> 00:18:47.000
[Guest]: You know, I obviously don't want to be morbid,

00:18:47.000 --> 00:18:49.000
[Guest]: but for instance, he also happened to die

00:18:49.000 --> 00:18:53.000
[Guest]: right before the economy took a turn for the worst.

00:18:53.000 --> 00:18:56.000
[Guest]: So even his exit was perfectly timed in terms of his legacy

00:18:56.000 --> 00:18:58.000
[Guest]: in the eyes of his supporters, right?

00:18:58.000 --> 00:19:00.000
[Amit Varma]: In fact, just looking through his career,

00:19:00.000 --> 00:19:02.000
[Amit Varma]: I mean, there are various parts where he got so lucky.

00:19:02.000 --> 00:19:05.000
[Amit Varma]: For example, he almost didn't get through into the army

00:19:05.000 --> 00:19:08.000
[Amit Varma]: because he failed his chemistry exam, right?

00:19:08.000 --> 00:19:10.000
[Amit Varma]: And had that not happened,

00:19:10.000 --> 00:19:12.000
[Amit Varma]: the subsequent events wouldn't have worked out the way they did.

00:19:12.000 --> 00:19:14.000
[Amit Varma]: That while in the army for years,

00:19:14.000 --> 00:19:16.000
[Amit Varma]: he wanted to overthrow the government,

00:19:16.000 --> 00:19:18.000
[Amit Varma]: not because he had anything against the government

00:19:18.000 --> 00:19:20.000
[Amit Varma]: or any particular precedent, but he just wanted to get to power.

00:19:20.000 --> 00:19:23.000
[Amit Varma]: And he was planning a coup as administrations changed one by one.

00:19:23.000 --> 00:19:27.000
[Amit Varma]: He's single-mindedly planning a coup for the sake of power itself.

00:19:27.000 --> 00:19:30.000
[Amit Varma]: And, you know, even when he, you know,

00:19:30.000 --> 00:19:33.000
[Amit Varma]: he attempted a coup in 1992 and he failed,

00:19:33.000 --> 00:19:36.000
[Amit Varma]: and he would have disappeared into oblivion and into prison.

00:19:36.000 --> 00:19:40.000
[Amit Varma]: He had the powers that be not decided to put him on television.

00:19:40.000 --> 00:19:43.000
[Amit Varma]: So he could tell his co-conspirators to surrender.

00:19:43.000 --> 00:19:45.000
[Amit Varma]: And he suddenly became a media star after that.

00:19:45.000 --> 00:19:46.000
[Guest]: Absolutely.

00:19:46.000 --> 00:19:49.000
[Guest]: I mean, he capitalized on those few minutes on television and said,

00:19:49.000 --> 00:19:52.000
[Guest]: we failed for ahora, for now,

00:19:52.000 --> 00:19:55.000
[Guest]: which became the slogan that everyone repeated.

00:19:55.000 --> 00:19:57.000
[Guest]: And then he was pardoned, of course,

00:19:57.000 --> 00:20:00.000
[Guest]: and got out and became a political figure in his own right.

00:20:00.000 --> 00:20:04.000
[Guest]: So yes, from the chemistry exam to being pardoned,

00:20:04.000 --> 00:20:06.000
[Amit Varma]: the stars aligned for him.

00:20:06.000 --> 00:20:08.000
[Amit Varma]: And it's interesting how, you know,

00:20:08.000 --> 00:20:12.000
[Amit Varma]: people close to him talk about how his personality changed so suddenly

00:20:12.000 --> 00:20:14.000
[Amit Varma]: at two different parts of his life.

00:20:14.000 --> 00:20:17.000
[Amit Varma]: One is once he comes on television and he becomes a superstar,

00:20:17.000 --> 00:20:19.000
[Amit Varma]: and he literally becomes a sex symbol.

00:20:19.000 --> 00:20:22.000
[Amit Varma]: Women everywhere are dying to have his baby, so to say,

00:20:22.000 --> 00:20:24.000
[Amit Varma]: as one biographer put it.

00:20:24.000 --> 00:20:26.000
[Amit Varma]: And the other when he actually comes to power,

00:20:26.000 --> 00:20:29.000
[Amit Varma]: that, you know, when he comes to power and he, you know,

00:20:29.000 --> 00:20:31.000
[Amit Varma]: enters Miraflores, I think the presidential palace,

00:20:31.000 --> 00:20:35.000
[Amit Varma]: he just becomes a completely different person and his allies from the period

00:20:35.000 --> 00:20:39.000
[Amit Varma]: before that eventually all get disillusioned one by one and move on.

00:20:39.000 --> 00:20:42.000
[Guest]: And he ends up surrounding himself with yes-men.

00:20:42.000 --> 00:20:44.000
[Amit Varma]: And he ends up surrounding himself with yes-men.

00:20:44.000 --> 00:20:47.000
[Amit Varma]: And, you know, if you look at Maduro today,

00:20:47.000 --> 00:20:49.000
[Amit Varma]: just reading the biographies of Chavez,

00:20:49.000 --> 00:20:53.000
[Amit Varma]: the one thing that kind of struck me is that the only extraordinary thing

00:20:53.000 --> 00:20:56.000
[Amit Varma]: about Maduro is that he never said no to Chavez,

00:20:56.000 --> 00:21:00.000
[Amit Varma]: that he was almost like, you know,

00:21:00.000 --> 00:21:03.000
[Amit Varma]: like again Indira Gandhi said about a former president of ours,

00:21:03.000 --> 00:21:06.000
[Amit Varma]: Gyani Zayal Singh, before he became president,

00:21:06.000 --> 00:21:08.000
[Amit Varma]: that if I ask him to clean my toilets, he will.

00:21:08.000 --> 00:21:13.000
[Amit Varma]: And you get the same kind of sense about sort of Chavez and Maduro.

00:21:13.000 --> 00:21:17.000
[Amit Varma]: And that's really the reason Maduro kind of got to power to begin with.

00:21:17.000 --> 00:21:20.000
[Guest]: Yes. I mean, he describes himself as the son of Chavez.

00:21:20.000 --> 00:21:24.000
[Guest]: He stakes his entire legacy on Chavez.

00:21:24.000 --> 00:21:27.000
[Amit Varma]: Right. So again, extraordinary luck for Maduro as well.

00:21:27.000 --> 00:21:32.000
[Amit Varma]: Tell me a little bit about the confluence of oil and politics

00:21:32.000 --> 00:21:35.000
[Amit Varma]: through the decades in Venezuela.

00:21:35.000 --> 00:21:37.000
[Amit Varma]: Like, obviously, they discover oil, they're very lucky.

00:21:37.000 --> 00:21:39.000
[Amit Varma]: Then they come to these deals where, for example,

00:21:39.000 --> 00:21:42.000
[Amit Varma]: these foreign companies first come and they start taking the oil.

00:21:42.000 --> 00:21:45.000
[Amit Varma]: And then they have these 50-50 arrangements where they get,

00:21:45.000 --> 00:21:48.000
[Amit Varma]: share 50% of the profits with the state.

00:21:48.000 --> 00:21:50.000
[Amit Varma]: And then that tilts further to the state.

00:21:50.000 --> 00:21:54.000
[Amit Varma]: And then it's Venezuela, which actually forms OPEC.

00:21:54.000 --> 00:21:57.000
[Amit Varma]: So all the power goes to the sort of –

00:21:57.000 --> 00:21:59.000
[Amit Varma]: that actually pushes for the formation of OPEC.

00:21:59.000 --> 00:22:04.000
[Amit Varma]: So all the power goes to the states rather than the companies.

00:22:04.000 --> 00:22:07.000
[Amit Varma]: And then gradually that in the mid-'70s leads to the formation

00:22:07.000 --> 00:22:09.000
[Amit Varma]: of the state oil company PVDSA.

00:22:09.000 --> 00:22:12.000
[Amit Varma]: So tell me a little bit about the role oil played in politics

00:22:12.000 --> 00:22:14.000
[Amit Varma]: through the decades.

00:22:14.000 --> 00:22:18.000
[Guest]: Yes. Well, oil is indistinguishable from Venezuela.

00:22:18.000 --> 00:22:23.000
[Guest]: And the Venezuelan economy has always been hugely dependent on oil.

00:22:23.000 --> 00:22:26.000
[Guest]: You mentioned the Dutch disease, and that impeded Venezuela

00:22:26.000 --> 00:22:29.000
[Guest]: from having enough efficient industry and agriculture,

00:22:29.000 --> 00:22:33.000
[Guest]: although it did have those sectors in the 70s and 80s.

00:22:33.000 --> 00:22:37.000
[Guest]: But Chávez's big criticism was that the foreign companies

00:22:37.000 --> 00:22:42.000
[Guest]: were getting too sweet a deal in Venezuela under the former governments.

00:22:42.000 --> 00:22:45.000
[Guest]: And so very quickly, when he comes to power,

00:22:45.000 --> 00:22:48.000
[Guest]: he understands that PVDSA, the state oil company,

00:22:48.000 --> 00:22:50.000
[Guest]: will be crucial to his fortunes.

00:22:50.000 --> 00:22:54.000
[Guest]: And, in fact, the lead-up to the coup, there's a strike

00:22:54.000 --> 00:22:57.000
[Guest]: by PVDSA workers and engineers against Chávez.

00:22:57.000 --> 00:23:00.000
[Guest]: So they bring the oil industry to a standstill,

00:23:00.000 --> 00:23:04.000
[Guest]: which again shocks the oil market and completely attacks

00:23:04.000 --> 00:23:06.000
[Guest]: the Venezuelan economy.

00:23:06.000 --> 00:23:09.000
[Guest]: And ultimately, as we know, Chávez prevails,

00:23:09.000 --> 00:23:13.000
[Guest]: and he absolutely purges the state oil company.

00:23:13.000 --> 00:23:16.000
[Guest]: And so all these engineers who supported the opposition

00:23:16.000 --> 00:23:18.000
[Guest]: and walked off their jobs are fired.

00:23:18.000 --> 00:23:20.000
[Guest]: There's huge turnover.

00:23:20.000 --> 00:23:22.000
[Guest]: A lot of these people incidentally ended up immigrating

00:23:22.000 --> 00:23:25.000
[Guest]: to Colombia or Canada and helping basically create

00:23:25.000 --> 00:23:30.000
[Guest]: the Colombian oil industry, so benefiting other countries.

00:23:30.000 --> 00:23:35.000
[Guest]: And gradually, over time, PVDSA becomes a fiefdom for Chavismo.

00:23:35.000 --> 00:23:39.000
[Guest]: For a long time, it maintains operational capacity,

00:23:39.000 --> 00:23:43.000
[Guest]: even though it's highly indebted, inefficient, and corrupt,

00:23:43.000 --> 00:23:48.000
[Guest]: but it still kind of has the veneer of a functional company.

00:23:48.000 --> 00:23:53.000
[Guest]: But throughout my time there, you just saw it close off.

00:23:53.000 --> 00:23:57.000
[Guest]: And in the last year, Maduro put a general in charge

00:23:57.000 --> 00:24:01.000
[Guest]: of the state oil company because the military is absolutely

00:24:01.000 --> 00:24:04.000
[Guest]: the other kind of crucial part to understanding Venezuela.

00:24:04.000 --> 00:24:08.000
[Guest]: And generals have been sweetened by all these deals

00:24:08.000 --> 00:24:11.000
[Guest]: that Maduro's offered them, you know, mining stakes,

00:24:11.000 --> 00:24:13.000
[Guest]: control over imports, and the oil industry,

00:24:13.000 --> 00:24:16.000
[Guest]: which is the crown jewel, as a way of rewarding them

00:24:16.000 --> 00:24:18.000
[Guest]: for their loyalty and ensuring that they continue

00:24:18.000 --> 00:24:20.000
[Guest]: to be loyal to him.

00:24:20.000 --> 00:24:25.000
[Guest]: And it's led to an exodus of your low-level workers

00:24:25.000 --> 00:24:27.000
[Guest]: who are already unable to eat three square meals a day

00:24:27.000 --> 00:24:30.000
[Guest]: because they're just earning a handful of dollars a month.

00:24:30.000 --> 00:24:34.000
[Guest]: Of course, you know, any engineer or chemist has fled

00:24:34.000 --> 00:24:36.000
[Guest]: because they're not earning anything more.

00:24:36.000 --> 00:24:39.000
[Guest]: They're often working in dangerous refineries

00:24:39.000 --> 00:24:41.000
[Guest]: that haven't had proper maintenance work in years

00:24:41.000 --> 00:24:43.000
[Guest]: and are a big threat.

00:24:43.000 --> 00:24:46.000
[Guest]: And it's also actually very dangerous out in the oil fields

00:24:46.000 --> 00:24:50.000
[Guest]: because large parts of Venezuela are essentially lawless.

00:24:50.000 --> 00:24:54.000
[Guest]: And you're very exposed to theft and gangs looking

00:24:54.000 --> 00:24:58.000
[Guest]: to rob copper or rob you in the oil installations.

00:24:58.000 --> 00:25:01.000
[Guest]: So the whole industry is completely unraveled,

00:25:01.000 --> 00:25:05.000
[Guest]: which is a huge threat for Maduro given that more than 90%

00:25:05.000 --> 00:25:08.000
[Guest]: of the income, the country, comes from oil now

00:25:08.000 --> 00:25:12.000
[Guest]: because all the other industries have fallen by the wayside.

00:25:12.000 --> 00:25:15.000
[Guest]: And now, with the new sanctions from the Trump administration,

00:25:15.000 --> 00:25:18.000
[Guest]: it's getting even harder for him to export oil.

00:25:18.000 --> 00:25:21.000
[Guest]: So yet again, oil will be one of the big deciding factors

00:25:21.000 --> 00:25:23.000
[Amit Varma]: in what happens in Venezuela.

00:25:23.000 --> 00:25:27.000
[Amit Varma]: And this process was, like, it's common to all populists, really,

00:25:27.000 --> 00:25:30.000
[Amit Varma]: that they attack the institutions in their countries

00:25:30.000 --> 00:25:32.000
[Amit Varma]: which are supposed to act as checks and balances.

00:25:32.000 --> 00:25:35.000
[Amit Varma]: And again, one of the things that Chávez did when he came to power

00:25:35.000 --> 00:25:37.000
[Amit Varma]: is that he put military officers everywhere.

00:25:37.000 --> 00:25:39.000
[Amit Varma]: So, you know, this whole trend of...

00:25:39.000 --> 00:25:42.000
[Amit Varma]: So even in the PDVSA, after the strike happened

00:25:42.000 --> 00:25:44.000
[Amit Varma]: and he laid off all the employees or whatever,

00:25:44.000 --> 00:25:46.000
[Amit Varma]: he then put military officers in charge

00:25:46.000 --> 00:25:49.000
[Amit Varma]: and completely changed the way the institution worked

00:25:49.000 --> 00:25:53.000
[Amit Varma]: in terms of sort of doing what people call petro-diplomacy,

00:25:53.000 --> 00:25:57.000
[Amit Varma]: where he would, you know, offer sweet deals to neighboring countries

00:25:57.000 --> 00:26:01.000
[Amit Varma]: which had communist leaders he was friendly with to get them on his side.

00:26:01.000 --> 00:26:04.000
[Amit Varma]: And a large chunk of petrodollars, therefore,

00:26:04.000 --> 00:26:07.000
[Amit Varma]: started going into this kind of diplomacy

00:26:07.000 --> 00:26:10.000
[Amit Varma]: and doing special favors to people and so on and so forth.

00:26:10.000 --> 00:26:15.000
[Guest]: Exactly. Cuba has been one of the big recipients of this petro-diplomacy.

00:26:15.000 --> 00:26:19.000
[Guest]: You know, Venezuela still sends oil to Cuba

00:26:19.000 --> 00:26:21.000
[Guest]: and Cuba, quote-unquote, repays Venezuela

00:26:21.000 --> 00:26:26.000
[Guest]: by sending doctors and other security personnel to the country

00:26:26.000 --> 00:26:30.000
[Guest]: in what Maduro's critics say is a grossly unfair trade-off.

00:26:30.000 --> 00:26:33.000
[Guest]: And especially because it's fairly well-known in Cuba,

00:26:33.000 --> 00:26:37.000
[Guest]: then Cuba then resells a lot of the oil it receives from Venezuela for profit.

00:26:37.000 --> 00:26:41.000
[Amit Varma]: Which is a marvelously capitalistic thing for Cuba to do.

00:26:41.000 --> 00:26:46.000
[Amit Varma]: And let's talk about what happened to the currency, for example.

00:26:46.000 --> 00:26:49.000
[Amit Varma]: So, you know, one of the books you recommended I read

00:26:49.000 --> 00:26:52.000
[Amit Varma]: before we do this podcast was Crude Nation by Raúl Gallegos

00:26:52.000 --> 00:26:54.000
[Amit Varma]: and that starts off with this fascinating chapter

00:26:54.000 --> 00:26:56.000
[Amit Varma]: on how there are four currency rates,

00:26:56.000 --> 00:26:59.000
[Amit Varma]: like three different official currency rates for the dollars

00:26:59.000 --> 00:27:01.000
[Amit Varma]: and then there's another one which is black market

00:27:01.000 --> 00:27:05.000
[Amit Varma]: and the top rate is like you pay a handful of bolivars for a dollar

00:27:05.000 --> 00:27:08.000
[Amit Varma]: and then you increasingly pay more and more bolivars

00:27:08.000 --> 00:27:12.000
[Amit Varma]: and obviously your cronies and people you favor get them at the cheapest rate

00:27:12.000 --> 00:27:15.000
[Amit Varma]: and there's a whole industry where you're sort of, you know,

00:27:15.000 --> 00:27:18.000
[Amit Varma]: buying dollars in the cheap and selling dollars in the black market

00:27:18.000 --> 00:27:20.000
[Amit Varma]: for far more money.

00:27:20.000 --> 00:27:23.000
[Amit Varma]: When you landed up there, how was it? How did you manage?

00:27:23.000 --> 00:27:27.000
[Guest]: Well, it's an extraordinary system that you end up being very agile in

00:27:27.000 --> 00:27:30.000
[Guest]: because you're always jumping between different currency systems.

00:27:30.000 --> 00:27:33.000
[Guest]: But when I arrived, first of all, your bank card doesn't work.

00:27:33.000 --> 00:27:34.000
[Guest]: No foreign cards work.

00:27:34.000 --> 00:27:38.000
[Guest]: You could take money out but at an extraordinarily unfavorable rate

00:27:38.000 --> 00:27:40.000
[Guest]: so you'd be getting a dollar out,

00:27:40.000 --> 00:27:43.000
[Guest]: effectively getting what's worth a dollar on the black market

00:27:43.000 --> 00:27:46.000
[Guest]: but spending maybe $50 for it in your bank account.

00:27:46.000 --> 00:27:49.000
[Guest]: So what someone like me or others get is a middleman, right,

00:27:49.000 --> 00:27:54.000
[Guest]: who you wire money to from your bank account abroad to his bank account abroad

00:27:54.000 --> 00:27:58.000
[Guest]: and then he wires bolivares from his account to your account in Venezuela

00:27:58.000 --> 00:28:01.000
[Guest]: and that allows you to navigate the system.

00:28:01.000 --> 00:28:04.000
[Guest]: But it creates an enormous amount of distortions.

00:28:04.000 --> 00:28:08.000
[Guest]: So, for instance, for a long time, foreign airlines priced their airfare

00:28:08.000 --> 00:28:12.000
[Guest]: in local currency but at the pegged official rate.

00:28:12.000 --> 00:28:17.000
[Guest]: So that meant people could fly literally from Caracas to London

00:28:17.000 --> 00:28:20.000
[Guest]: for the equivalent of $40 if they were buying their currency

00:28:20.000 --> 00:28:21.000
[Guest]: on the black market, right?

00:28:21.000 --> 00:28:22.000
[Guest]: So it was a free-for-all.

00:28:22.000 --> 00:28:25.000
[Guest]: It was this bizarre distorted party that people were taking care of.

00:28:25.000 --> 00:28:27.000
[Guest]: Of course, someone has to pick up the bill

00:28:27.000 --> 00:28:31.000
[Guest]: and foreign airlines are now owed a total of about $4 billion

00:28:31.000 --> 00:28:35.000
[Guest]: because the Venezuelan government never then reimbursed them as promised.

00:28:35.000 --> 00:28:38.000
[Guest]: So that's the kind of distorted magical realism side of it.

00:28:38.000 --> 00:28:42.000
[Guest]: The real-world impact of it is that nothing worked, right,

00:28:42.000 --> 00:28:44.000
[Guest]: because what you're supposed to trust, which is money,

00:28:44.000 --> 00:28:47.000
[Guest]: which has a certain value and creates trust and creates your chain,

00:28:47.000 --> 00:28:49.000
[Guest]: was completely distorted.

00:28:49.000 --> 00:28:51.000
[Guest]: So things just didn't function.

00:28:51.000 --> 00:28:55.000
[Guest]: Importers wouldn't import because they wouldn't have access

00:28:55.000 --> 00:28:58.000
[Guest]: to the official currency because that was reserved for cronies

00:28:58.000 --> 00:29:01.000
[Guest]: and so had to go to the black market rate if they could afford it

00:29:01.000 --> 00:29:03.000
[Guest]: and then pass that cost on to customers.

00:29:03.000 --> 00:29:05.000
[Guest]: If not, they folded shop.

00:29:05.000 --> 00:29:09.000
[Guest]: So that was really the deathblow to the Venezuelan economy,

00:29:09.000 --> 00:29:11.000
[Guest]: the incredible distortions in the currency.

00:29:11.000 --> 00:29:13.000
[Amit Varma]: And then this differing access to the dollar

00:29:13.000 --> 00:29:16.000
[Amit Varma]: then creates different classes of people, right?

00:29:16.000 --> 00:29:17.000
[Guest]: Absolutely.

00:29:17.000 --> 00:29:19.000
[Guest]: I mean, the Venezuelans have a lot of vernacular

00:29:19.000 --> 00:29:21.000
[Guest]: for what has happened in the last 10 years

00:29:21.000 --> 00:29:24.000
[Guest]: and there's an expression which is boliburgues.

00:29:24.000 --> 00:29:28.000
[Guest]: So it's a play on burguesia, so the bourgeoisie,

00:29:28.000 --> 00:29:30.000
[Guest]: and boli being bolivariano,

00:29:30.000 --> 00:29:33.000
[Guest]: which is this kind of following that Chávez created

00:29:33.000 --> 00:29:35.000
[Guest]: based on Simón Bolívar.

00:29:35.000 --> 00:29:37.000
[Guest]: So basically, these are the new rich,

00:29:37.000 --> 00:29:40.000
[Guest]: those who benefited from the government's largesse.

00:29:40.000 --> 00:29:42.000
[Guest]: The other term for them is enchufados,

00:29:42.000 --> 00:29:44.000
[Guest]: so those who are plugged in.

00:29:44.000 --> 00:29:45.000
[Guest]: That's essentially what they are.

00:29:45.000 --> 00:29:46.000
[Guest]: They're plugged into the system,

00:29:46.000 --> 00:29:49.000
[Guest]: so they get dollars at a preferential rate.

00:29:49.000 --> 00:29:52.000
[Guest]: Their companies can be signed into the system to import food

00:29:52.000 --> 00:29:55.000
[Guest]: and get the juicy government contracts, etc., etc.

