00:31:21.000 --> 00:31:23.000
[Amit Varma]: Welcome back to The Scene and The Unseen.

00:31:23.000 --> 00:31:26.000
[Amit Varma]: I'm chatting with Alexandra Ulmer about Venezuela.

00:31:26.000 --> 00:31:30.000
[Amit Varma]: I mean, the other thing everybody sort of notices about Venezuela

00:31:30.000 --> 00:31:32.000
[Amit Varma]: is the mad inflation.

00:31:32.000 --> 00:31:34.000
[Amit Varma]: You know, now it's at crazy levels,

00:31:34.000 --> 00:31:37.000
[Amit Varma]: but even under Chavez, it was at like 60% a year,

00:31:37.000 --> 00:31:38.000
[Amit Varma]: and it would balloon.

00:31:38.000 --> 00:31:40.000
[Amit Varma]: And one of the things that I realized was,

00:31:40.000 --> 00:31:44.000
[Amit Varma]: one, that inflation has been a common part of Venezuela

00:31:44.000 --> 00:31:48.000
[Amit Varma]: for decades, not just a Chavez issue.

00:31:48.000 --> 00:31:52.000
[Amit Varma]: And two, there's a quality which people often consider

00:31:52.000 --> 00:31:55.000
[Amit Varma]: a cultural quality, but which really seemed to me

00:31:55.000 --> 00:31:57.000
[Amit Varma]: to come out of economic imperatives,

00:31:57.000 --> 00:32:00.000
[Amit Varma]: in the sense that people often say that

00:32:00.000 --> 00:32:02.000
[Amit Varma]: so-and-so kind of people or so-and-so culture,

00:32:02.000 --> 00:32:04.000
[Unknown]: they are good savers, they like to save,

00:32:04.000 --> 00:32:06.000
[Amit Varma]: as if that's a cultural value.

00:32:06.000 --> 00:32:08.000
[Amit Varma]: But what inflation did to Venezuela was,

00:32:08.000 --> 00:32:09.000
[Amit Varma]: because inflation was so high,

00:32:09.000 --> 00:32:12.000
[Amit Varma]: it just made no rational sense to save.

00:32:12.000 --> 00:32:15.000
[Amit Varma]: And Venezuelans would, I mean, taking debt makes,

00:32:15.000 --> 00:32:18.000
[Amit Varma]: I mean, just to give an illustration of this,

00:32:18.000 --> 00:32:21.000
[Amit Varma]: you could buy a house today at regular EMIs,

00:32:21.000 --> 00:32:25.000
[Amit Varma]: and a year later, your EMIs would really be

00:32:25.000 --> 00:32:28.000
[Amit Varma]: as much as you are paying to buy a loaf of bread.

00:32:28.000 --> 00:32:32.000
[Amit Varma]: So it makes, so the moment, whatever debt you can get,

00:32:32.000 --> 00:32:33.000
[Amit Varma]: people would take it, you know,

00:32:33.000 --> 00:32:35.000
[Amit Varma]: so even the poorest people would take debt

00:32:35.000 --> 00:32:37.000
[Amit Varma]: and buy flat-screen TVs and whatever

00:32:37.000 --> 00:32:39.000
[Amit Varma]: and spend it on consumer goods.

00:32:39.000 --> 00:32:41.000
[Amit Varma]: And it's not because of materialism gone mad

00:32:41.000 --> 00:32:43.000
[Amit Varma]: or consumerism or anything like that,

00:32:43.000 --> 00:32:47.000
[Amit Varma]: it's just that those are the economic incentives.

00:32:47.000 --> 00:32:50.000
[Amit Varma]: So it's like culture being driven by economics.

00:32:50.000 --> 00:32:52.000
[Guest]: And Latin Americans, historically,

00:32:52.000 --> 00:32:53.000
[Guest]: have not been considered good savers,

00:32:53.000 --> 00:32:55.000
[Guest]: but that's because they've, almost every country

00:32:55.000 --> 00:32:58.000
[Guest]: has had some kind of spate of inflation.

00:32:58.000 --> 00:33:00.000
[Guest]: Venezuela has pushed it to a whole other level, right?

00:33:00.000 --> 00:33:02.000
[Guest]: We're looking at 2 million percent,

00:33:02.000 --> 00:33:03.000
[Guest]: even though, as I mentioned,

00:33:03.000 --> 00:33:05.000
[Guest]: we don't have official government data.

00:33:05.000 --> 00:33:07.000
[Guest]: It's wild, and it's really the only thing

00:33:07.000 --> 00:33:10.000
[Guest]: people talk about because it is such a disorienting

00:33:10.000 --> 00:33:12.000
[Guest]: and life-destroying phenomenon.

00:33:12.000 --> 00:33:13.000
[Guest]: It destroys your salary.

00:33:13.000 --> 00:33:16.000
[Guest]: It's as if you walked into a supermarket tomorrow

00:33:16.000 --> 00:33:19.000
[Guest]: and a sack of rice was priced at 18,000 rupees.

00:33:19.000 --> 00:33:20.000
[Guest]: How can you talk about anything else?

00:33:20.000 --> 00:33:21.000
[Guest]: It's your livelihood.

00:33:21.000 --> 00:33:23.000
[Guest]: It's everything you thought was stable

00:33:23.000 --> 00:33:25.000
[Guest]: that is being cut out from under you.

00:33:25.000 --> 00:33:28.000
[Guest]: And what's particularly fascinating

00:33:28.000 --> 00:33:30.000
[Guest]: about this spate of hyperinflation

00:33:30.000 --> 00:33:33.000
[Guest]: is that it seems to be the first one of the digital age.

00:33:33.000 --> 00:33:36.000
[Guest]: So Venezuelan government can't even print

00:33:36.000 --> 00:33:39.000
[Guest]: enough physical money to keep up with the money

00:33:39.000 --> 00:33:42.000
[Guest]: it's creating in general.

00:33:42.000 --> 00:33:45.000
[Guest]: So there's a perennial shortage of bills.

00:33:45.000 --> 00:33:47.000
[Guest]: So prices are going up all the time,

00:33:47.000 --> 00:33:49.000
[Guest]: but no one has any physical money,

00:33:49.000 --> 00:33:51.000
[Guest]: which is insane because it's not the kind of

00:33:51.000 --> 00:33:55.000
[Guest]: wheelbarrow image you have of hyperinflation, right?

00:33:55.000 --> 00:33:56.000
[Guest]: So what does that mean?

00:33:56.000 --> 00:33:59.000
[Guest]: That means every ATM you walk in front of

00:33:59.000 --> 00:34:02.000
[Guest]: has tens of people queuing up at any given time

00:34:02.000 --> 00:34:04.000
[Guest]: hoping to get a few bills out,

00:34:04.000 --> 00:34:06.000
[Guest]: even though the maximum is about $2

00:34:06.000 --> 00:34:08.000
[Guest]: that you can take out of the ATM.

00:34:08.000 --> 00:34:09.000
[Amit Varma]: Which you can't buy anything with.

00:34:09.000 --> 00:34:10.000
[Guest]: You can't buy anything with that,

00:34:10.000 --> 00:34:12.000
[Guest]: especially when prices are changing every day.

00:34:12.000 --> 00:34:15.000
[Guest]: So you use your bank card.

00:34:15.000 --> 00:34:17.000
[Guest]: Wait, there's a catch there too.

00:34:17.000 --> 00:34:20.000
[Guest]: Venezuela hasn't invested in its telecom system

00:34:20.000 --> 00:34:22.000
[Guest]: and has fixed prices for years,

00:34:22.000 --> 00:34:24.000
[Guest]: so they're completely oversaturated

00:34:24.000 --> 00:34:27.000
[Guest]: and so point of sales collapse all the time.

00:34:27.000 --> 00:34:29.000
[Guest]: They're also rolling blackouts

00:34:29.000 --> 00:34:31.000
[Guest]: because ditto, no investment, no maintenance.

00:34:31.000 --> 00:34:35.000
[Guest]: So the power grid is incredibly shaky.

00:34:35.000 --> 00:34:37.000
[Guest]: Your phones, same issue.

00:34:37.000 --> 00:34:39.000
[Guest]: So there literally were times

00:34:39.000 --> 00:34:41.000
[Guest]: where I could not pay for something.

00:34:41.000 --> 00:34:43.000
[Guest]: I obviously had the money in my account.

00:34:43.000 --> 00:34:45.000
[Guest]: I wanted to pay for it, but nothing worked.

00:34:45.000 --> 00:34:46.000
[Guest]: I had no bills.

00:34:46.000 --> 00:34:48.000
[Guest]: The power system was down.

00:34:48.000 --> 00:34:50.000
[Guest]: The point of sale didn't work.

00:34:50.000 --> 00:34:51.000
[Guest]: And there's just no way to conduct

00:34:51.000 --> 00:34:53.000
[Guest]: a very basic economic transaction.

00:34:53.000 --> 00:34:55.000
[Amit Varma]: And just for my listeners' benefit,

00:34:55.000 --> 00:34:57.000
[Amit Varma]: to talk about the monetary basis of inflation,

00:34:57.000 --> 00:34:59.000
[Amit Varma]: what inflation is typically caused by

00:34:59.000 --> 00:35:01.000
[Amit Varma]: is when the money supply goes up

00:35:01.000 --> 00:35:03.000
[Amit Varma]: relative to the goods and services available.

00:35:03.000 --> 00:35:05.000
[Amit Varma]: So what happens is when a government decides

00:35:05.000 --> 00:35:07.000
[Amit Varma]: that it needs to up its spending

00:35:07.000 --> 00:35:09.000
[Amit Varma]: or pay back its debts or whatever

00:35:09.000 --> 00:35:11.000
[Amit Varma]: and it starts printing money,

00:35:11.000 --> 00:35:13.000
[Amit Varma]: the amount of money relative to goods and services

00:35:13.000 --> 00:35:15.000
[Amit Varma]: just goes up and therefore you have

00:35:15.000 --> 00:35:17.000
[Amit Varma]: more money chasing the same number of goods.

00:35:17.000 --> 00:35:19.000
[Amit Varma]: So obviously supply and demand,

00:35:19.000 --> 00:35:21.000
[Amit Varma]: the goods and services out there become more expensive.

00:35:21.000 --> 00:35:23.000
[Amit Varma]: And if you just keep indiscriminately

00:35:23.000 --> 00:35:25.000
[Amit Varma]: printing money,

00:35:25.000 --> 00:35:27.000
[Amit Varma]: this just gets worse and worse

00:35:27.000 --> 00:35:29.000
[Amit Varma]: till it spirals to, you know,

00:35:29.000 --> 00:35:31.000
[Amit Varma]: unmanageable proportions till, you know,

00:35:31.000 --> 00:35:33.000
[Amit Varma]: what you used to buy a house with.

00:35:33.000 --> 00:35:35.000
[Amit Varma]: One year later you buy a loaf of bread with that

00:35:35.000 --> 00:35:37.000
[Amit Varma]: and the poor are most

00:35:37.000 --> 00:35:39.000
[Amit Varma]: hurt by it. But what kind of surprises me is that

00:35:39.000 --> 00:35:41.000
[Amit Varma]: despite a lot of this happening for

00:35:41.000 --> 00:35:43.000
[Amit Varma]: even the early, since the start of

00:35:43.000 --> 00:35:45.000
[Amit Varma]: Chavez's regime in a sense,

00:35:45.000 --> 00:35:47.000
[Amit Varma]: he had popular support for

00:35:47.000 --> 00:35:49.000
[Amit Varma]: a much longer time than you would have.

00:35:49.000 --> 00:35:51.000
[Amit Varma]: I mean, is that because people

00:35:51.000 --> 00:35:53.000
[Amit Varma]: disconnect what is happening to them from

00:35:53.000 --> 00:35:55.000
[Amit Varma]: the economic policies

00:35:55.000 --> 00:35:57.000
[Amit Varma]: that a government carries out?

00:35:57.000 --> 00:35:59.000
[Guest]: I think what Chavez did masterfully

00:35:59.000 --> 00:36:01.000
[Guest]: was control the narrative.

00:36:01.000 --> 00:36:03.000
[Guest]: That's what he was the most successful

00:36:03.000 --> 00:36:05.000
[Guest]: politician to do. So he said

00:36:05.000 --> 00:36:07.000
[Guest]: that all the economic woes were to do with

00:36:07.000 --> 00:36:09.000
[Guest]: an economic war being waged

00:36:09.000 --> 00:36:11.000
[Guest]: against him and Maduro's

00:36:11.000 --> 00:36:13.000
[Guest]: government, right? So the evil

00:36:13.000 --> 00:36:15.000
[Guest]: businessmen are stockpiling

00:36:15.000 --> 00:36:17.000
[Guest]: goods, the evil businessmen

00:36:17.000 --> 00:36:19.000
[Guest]: are upping prices in

00:36:19.000 --> 00:36:21.000
[Guest]: a speculative manner to ruin your life,

00:36:21.000 --> 00:36:23.000
[Guest]: etc. And, you know,

00:36:23.000 --> 00:36:25.000
[Guest]: hyperinflation is an abstract

00:36:25.000 --> 00:36:27.000
[Guest]: concept and it's not that easy to understand.

00:36:27.000 --> 00:36:29.000
[Guest]: And if the government dominates the airwaves

00:36:29.000 --> 00:36:31.000
[Guest]: and you don't have a background in economics,

00:36:31.000 --> 00:36:33.000
[Guest]: or perhaps not a background

00:36:33.000 --> 00:36:35.000
[Guest]: in anything because you weren't able to pursue your

00:36:35.000 --> 00:36:37.000
[Guest]: education, it's actually much

00:36:37.000 --> 00:36:39.000
[Guest]: easier to blame a speculator.

00:36:39.000 --> 00:36:41.000
[Guest]: And once the situation became

00:36:41.000 --> 00:36:43.000
[Guest]: really difficult in Venezuela and we had

00:36:43.000 --> 00:36:45.000
[Guest]: those hundreds of people

00:36:45.000 --> 00:36:47.000
[Guest]: banging on supermarket doors,

00:36:47.000 --> 00:36:49.000
[Guest]: demanding food,

00:36:49.000 --> 00:36:51.000
[Guest]: which happened all the time,

00:36:51.000 --> 00:36:53.000
[Guest]: you had the creation of these

00:36:53.000 --> 00:36:55.000
[Guest]: men called bachakeros,

00:36:55.000 --> 00:36:57.000
[Guest]: which is actually a name that derives from

00:36:57.000 --> 00:36:59.000
[Guest]: ants that can carry a lot on its back,

00:36:59.000 --> 00:37:01.000
[Guest]: which is lovely poetry,

00:37:01.000 --> 00:37:03.000
[Guest]: but in practice was terrible, right?

00:37:03.000 --> 00:37:05.000
[Guest]: So these men who queue up,

00:37:05.000 --> 00:37:07.000
[Guest]: buy up products that they then resell

00:37:07.000 --> 00:37:09.000
[Guest]: at a heightened price, right? Because not everyone

00:37:09.000 --> 00:37:11.000
[Guest]: can stand in line all day

00:37:11.000 --> 00:37:13.000
[Guest]: waiting for food. They have to get

00:37:13.000 --> 00:37:15.000
[Guest]: to work and some of them do have disposable

00:37:15.000 --> 00:37:17.000
[Guest]: income to pay more. So

00:37:17.000 --> 00:37:19.000
[Guest]: it's a lot easier if you're

00:37:19.000 --> 00:37:21.000
[Guest]: poor, stuck in line for hours,

00:37:21.000 --> 00:37:23.000
[Guest]: waiting to buy a pack of pasta,

00:37:23.000 --> 00:37:25.000
[Guest]: and you see these

00:37:25.000 --> 00:37:27.000
[Guest]: bachakeros slip in line in front of you,

00:37:27.000 --> 00:37:29.000
[Guest]: threaten you, buy up the products,

00:37:29.000 --> 00:37:31.000
[Guest]: and then you see those same products on your street corner

00:37:31.000 --> 00:37:33.000
[Guest]: the next day for five times the price. Well, who's to blame?

00:37:33.000 --> 00:37:35.000
[Guest]: The bachakeros, right?

00:37:35.000 --> 00:37:37.000
[Guest]: Of course, bachakeros

00:37:37.000 --> 00:37:39.000
[Guest]: don't exist in countries where you have

00:37:39.000 --> 00:37:41.000
[Guest]: enough supply and you don't have controls,

00:37:41.000 --> 00:37:43.000
[Guest]: but that's harder to remember when

00:37:43.000 --> 00:37:45.000
[Guest]: you're in the thick of it and you want to survive.

00:37:45.000 --> 00:37:47.000
[Guest]: I'm speaking more about

00:37:47.000 --> 00:37:49.000
[Guest]: Maduro's time in this essence,

00:37:49.000 --> 00:37:51.000
[Guest]: but I think in Chavez it was similar. He dominated

00:37:51.000 --> 00:37:53.000
[Guest]: the narrative and there was an incredibly polarized country,

00:37:53.000 --> 00:37:55.000
[Guest]: right? Where it was us against them.

00:37:55.000 --> 00:37:57.000
[Amit Varma]: No, and also one thing all these guys fell

00:37:57.000 --> 00:37:59.000
[Amit Varma]: prey to, not just Maduro and Chavez,

00:37:59.000 --> 00:38:01.000
[Amit Varma]: but even before that, is the temptation

00:38:01.000 --> 00:38:03.000
[Amit Varma]: of price controls. Like you referred to magical realism

00:38:03.000 --> 00:38:05.000
[Amit Varma]: earlier, and price controls really are

00:38:05.000 --> 00:38:07.000
[Amit Varma]: magical thinking. If you fix the price of something

00:38:07.000 --> 00:38:09.000
[Amit Varma]: that's where it'll stay. But as we

00:38:09.000 --> 00:38:11.000
[Amit Varma]: know, price controls lead to shortages.

00:38:11.000 --> 00:38:13.000
[Amit Varma]: And then when you have shortages,

00:38:13.000 --> 00:38:15.000
[Amit Varma]: obviously the black market

00:38:15.000 --> 00:38:17.000
[Amit Varma]: gets involved, as

00:38:17.000 --> 00:38:19.000
[Amit Varma]: you mentioned. And a lot of the problem in

00:38:19.000 --> 00:38:21.000
[Amit Varma]: Venezuela was, the way

00:38:21.000 --> 00:38:23.000
[Amit Varma]: I understood it, was driven not just by the rampant

00:38:23.000 --> 00:38:25.000
[Amit Varma]: inflation, but also then because

00:38:25.000 --> 00:38:27.000
[Amit Varma]: inflation put the prices of

00:38:27.000 --> 00:38:29.000
[Amit Varma]: goods out of reach of many people.

00:38:29.000 --> 00:38:31.000
[Amit Varma]: Chavez and then Maduro reacted

00:38:31.000 --> 00:38:33.000
[Amit Varma]: by imposing price controls,

00:38:33.000 --> 00:38:35.000
[Amit Varma]: which completely changed the incentives

00:38:35.000 --> 00:38:37.000
[Amit Varma]: for manufacturers who wouldn't manufacture

00:38:37.000 --> 00:38:39.000
[Amit Varma]: anymore, and the domestic manufacturing industry

00:38:39.000 --> 00:38:41.000
[Amit Varma]: died anyway. And

00:38:41.000 --> 00:38:43.000
[Amit Varma]: therefore goods became

00:38:43.000 --> 00:38:45.000
[Guest]: extremely scarce. Exactly.

00:38:45.000 --> 00:38:47.000
[Guest]: It created a negative food bag loop,

00:38:47.000 --> 00:38:49.000
[Guest]: where inflation would be up, the government would

00:38:49.000 --> 00:38:51.000
[Guest]: panic and decide to take

00:38:51.000 --> 00:38:53.000
[Guest]: corrective measures. So Maduro would

00:38:53.000 --> 00:38:55.000
[Guest]: come on TV, as he does almost every day,

00:38:55.000 --> 00:38:57.000
[Guest]: because that's how he governs, through the television,

00:38:57.000 --> 00:38:59.000
[Guest]: and announce a 35%

00:38:59.000 --> 00:39:01.000
[Guest]: wage increase to

00:39:01.000 --> 00:39:03.000
[Guest]: tackle hyperinflation, for instance, which

00:39:03.000 --> 00:39:05.000
[Guest]: meant that in turn, everyone had to increase the

00:39:05.000 --> 00:39:07.000
[Guest]: prices of the goods or services they were offering.

00:39:07.000 --> 00:39:09.000
[Amit Varma]: Because the wage increase came from basically

00:39:09.000 --> 00:39:11.000
[Guest]: printing money. Exactly. And then the

00:39:11.000 --> 00:39:13.000
[Guest]: shop owners have to pay their employees more, right?

00:39:13.000 --> 00:39:15.000
[Guest]: And so then, they even had

00:39:15.000 --> 00:39:17.000
[Guest]: this, they still do, have a

00:39:17.000 --> 00:39:19.000
[Guest]: superintendence of fair prices.

00:39:19.000 --> 00:39:21.000
[Guest]: They have inspectors that are sent out,

00:39:21.000 --> 00:39:23.000
[Guest]: often with a state TV camera trailing behind

00:39:23.000 --> 00:39:25.000
[Guest]: them, and they inspect the evil

00:39:25.000 --> 00:39:27.000
[Guest]: businessmen and, you know,

00:39:27.000 --> 00:39:29.000
[Guest]: fine them, arrest them, or whatever, if

00:39:29.000 --> 00:39:31.000
[Guest]: they feel like they're price gouging.

00:39:31.000 --> 00:39:33.000
[Guest]: And so, of course, you know,

00:39:33.000 --> 00:39:35.000
[Guest]: how does your business survive

00:39:35.000 --> 00:39:37.000
[Amit Varma]: in those conditions? And you have

00:39:37.000 --> 00:39:39.000
[Amit Varma]: to raise prices, and yet at the same time,

00:39:39.000 --> 00:39:41.000
[Amit Varma]: and you know, another trend that I noticed, which again

00:39:41.000 --> 00:39:43.000
[Amit Varma]: became much worse under Chavez,

00:39:43.000 --> 00:39:45.000
[Amit Varma]: was expropriations, where the government would just

00:39:45.000 --> 00:39:47.000
[Amit Varma]: say, okay, these private businesses

00:39:47.000 --> 00:39:49.000
[Amit Varma]: are, you know, cannibals, and we're

00:39:49.000 --> 00:39:51.000
[Amit Varma]: just going to take them over. And, you know,

00:39:51.000 --> 00:39:53.000
[Amit Varma]: there's, one of this even happened live on television,

00:39:53.000 --> 00:39:55.000
[Amit Varma]: where he went to the square in

00:39:55.000 --> 00:39:57.000
[Amit Varma]: Caracas, and he asked the mayor

00:39:57.000 --> 00:39:59.000
[Amit Varma]: of that area with him that,

00:39:59.000 --> 00:40:01.000
[Amit Varma]: you know, what is that shop? And he points

00:40:01.000 --> 00:40:03.000
[Amit Varma]: to one building, and those are the jewellery stores,

00:40:03.000 --> 00:40:05.000
[Amit Varma]: and he says, expropriate them.

00:40:05.000 --> 00:40:07.000
[Amit Varma]: And before the show is over, the guy has

00:40:07.000 --> 00:40:09.000
[Amit Varma]: bought the papers, and he signed them.

00:40:09.000 --> 00:40:11.000
[Amit Varma]: And then in the middle of the night, the store owners come

00:40:11.000 --> 00:40:13.000
[Amit Varma]: to take the jewellery in cardboard boxes.

00:40:13.000 --> 00:40:15.000
[Amit Varma]: And, you know, then

00:40:15.000 --> 00:40:17.000
[Amit Varma]: the reporter who wrote about this says that a year

00:40:17.000 --> 00:40:19.000
[Amit Varma]: later, there was absolutely, I think this was Rory

00:40:19.000 --> 00:40:21.000
[Unknown]: Gallagher in his book, Comandante, that

00:40:21.000 --> 00:40:23.000
[Amit Varma]: a year later, the building is just empty, and there's

00:40:23.000 --> 00:40:25.000
[Amit Varma]: absolutely nothing there, and it's all gone to waste.

00:40:25.000 --> 00:40:27.000
[Guest]: Right. So I think you're hitting on a

00:40:27.000 --> 00:40:29.000
[Guest]: very important point there, because, yes,

00:40:29.000 --> 00:40:31.000
[Guest]: there were flawed policies in the Maduro

00:40:31.000 --> 00:40:33.000
[Guest]: government, in the Chavez government, and yes, there

00:40:33.000 --> 00:40:35.000
[Guest]: was a lot of corruption. But one of the main

00:40:35.000 --> 00:40:37.000
[Guest]: characteristics of their governance was just incompetence.

00:40:37.000 --> 00:40:39.000
[Guest]: Right? Because there are ways

00:40:39.000 --> 00:40:41.000
[Guest]: of nationalising, compensating

00:40:41.000 --> 00:40:43.000
[Guest]: whoever was nationalised,

00:40:43.000 --> 00:40:45.000
[Guest]: and putting together a structure to keep

00:40:45.000 --> 00:40:47.000
[Guest]: that going. But

00:40:47.000 --> 00:40:49.000
[Guest]: this was just Chavez on TV saying

00:40:49.000 --> 00:40:51.000
[Guest]: expropriado. And there

00:40:51.000 --> 00:40:53.000
[Guest]: was no follow-up, and there was no

00:40:53.000 --> 00:40:55.000
[Guest]: attempt to really create a structure. So this happened

00:40:55.000 --> 00:40:57.000
[Guest]: in factories, in

00:40:57.000 --> 00:40:59.000
[Guest]: farms, jewellery stores, just

00:40:59.000 --> 00:41:01.000
[Guest]: deserted, abandoned,

00:41:01.000 --> 00:41:03.000
[Guest]: and it's just so wasteful

00:41:03.000 --> 00:41:05.000
[Amit Varma]: and heartbreaking. So you're saying

00:41:05.000 --> 00:41:07.000
[Amit Varma]: is it then the case, just thinking

00:41:07.000 --> 00:41:09.000
[Amit Varma]: aloud, that it's not even happening for

00:41:09.000 --> 00:41:11.000
[Amit Varma]: ideological reasons, which would be bad enough,

00:41:11.000 --> 00:41:13.000
[Amit Varma]: but just out of Chavez's showmanship,

00:41:13.000 --> 00:41:15.000
[Amit Varma]: you know, to create those kind of optics, and

00:41:15.000 --> 00:41:17.000
[Amit Varma]: to feed into his narrative, that, you know, private guy

00:41:17.000 --> 00:41:19.000
[Amit Varma]: bad, and I'm your saviour, and I'm going to save you all.

00:41:19.000 --> 00:41:21.000
[Guest]: You know, I had the distinct

00:41:21.000 --> 00:41:23.000
[Guest]: impression that everything at

00:41:23.000 --> 00:41:25.000
[Guest]: a certain point in Venezuela was just

00:41:25.000 --> 00:41:27.000
[Guest]: being governed, it was governance through

00:41:27.000 --> 00:41:29.000
[Guest]: television. That's not only because I had the

00:41:29.000 --> 00:41:31.000
[Guest]: unfortunate luck of being a journalist there, meaning I had to

00:41:31.000 --> 00:41:33.000
[Guest]: watch state TV day in, day out, which

00:41:33.000 --> 00:41:35.000
[Guest]: killed my neurons. But Maduro

00:41:35.000 --> 00:41:37.000
[Guest]: comes on television every day to speak,

00:41:37.000 --> 00:41:39.000
[Guest]: just like Chavez did, and that

00:41:39.000 --> 00:41:41.000
[Guest]: becomes, you know, a proxy

00:41:41.000 --> 00:41:43.000
[Guest]: for governance, you know, a flawed one, of

00:41:43.000 --> 00:41:45.000
[Guest]: course, that becomes the be-all, end-all,

00:41:45.000 --> 00:41:47.000
[Amit Varma]: controlling the narrative.

00:41:47.000 --> 00:41:49.000
[Amit Varma]: And how did kind of, like Chavez

00:41:49.000 --> 00:41:51.000
[Amit Varma]: seems to me, like you pointed out, he

00:41:51.000 --> 00:41:53.000
[Amit Varma]: kind of died, treated by doctors

00:41:53.000 --> 00:41:55.000
[Amit Varma]: in Cuba. He died before

00:41:55.000 --> 00:41:57.000
[Amit Varma]: the oil prices fell, and

00:41:57.000 --> 00:41:59.000
[Amit Varma]: you know, but Maduro effectively

00:41:59.000 --> 00:42:01.000
[Amit Varma]: was following out exactly the same kind of

00:42:01.000 --> 00:42:03.000
[Amit Varma]: policies, and what has happened to Maduro, I imagine

00:42:03.000 --> 00:42:05.000
[Amit Varma]: would have happened to Chavez,

00:42:05.000 --> 00:42:07.000
[Amit Varma]: but what was the kind of change that, I mean, and

00:42:07.000 --> 00:42:09.000
[Amit Varma]: those are the years where you

00:42:09.000 --> 00:42:11.000
[Amit Varma]: enter the story, and you know, 2014

00:42:11.000 --> 00:42:13.000
[Amit Varma]: onwards you've been there, and

00:42:13.000 --> 00:42:15.000
[Amit Varma]: so what really happened?

00:42:15.000 --> 00:42:17.000
[Amit Varma]: Take me through these last five years.

00:42:17.000 --> 00:42:19.000
[Guest]: Sure. So

00:42:19.000 --> 00:42:21.000
[Guest]: Maduro is very narrowly elected

00:42:21.000 --> 00:42:23.000
[Guest]: in a very controversial vote

00:42:23.000 --> 00:42:25.000
[Guest]: where the opposition still maintains

00:42:25.000 --> 00:42:27.000
[Guest]: it actually won.

00:42:27.000 --> 00:42:29.000
[Guest]: We're talking about the actual numbers

00:42:29.000 --> 00:42:31.000
[Amit Varma]: around the whole vote, of course.

00:42:31.000 --> 00:42:33.000
[Guest]: As in they're talking about the elections were rigged, basically.

00:42:33.000 --> 00:42:35.000
[Guest]: They were tweaked. That's what the opposition claims.

00:42:35.000 --> 00:42:37.000
[Guest]: Undeniably,

00:42:37.000 --> 00:42:39.000
[Guest]: the government used the state to its

00:42:39.000 --> 00:42:41.000
[Guest]: advantage, so busing people in, changing voting

00:42:41.000 --> 00:42:43.000
[Guest]: centers, all sorts of dirty tricks, but there's

00:42:43.000 --> 00:42:45.000
[Guest]: still a question as to whether the actual numbers were tweaked.

00:42:45.000 --> 00:42:47.000
[Guest]: So

00:42:47.000 --> 00:42:49.000
[Guest]: he gets elected with, you know, very slim

00:42:49.000 --> 00:42:51.000
[Guest]: majority and little

00:42:51.000 --> 00:42:53.000
[Guest]: credibility. As you said,

00:42:53.000 --> 00:42:55.000
[Guest]: he was a yes man to Chavez, a former

00:42:55.000 --> 00:42:57.000
[Guest]: bus driver and union leader

00:42:57.000 --> 00:42:59.000
[Guest]: who, you know, didn't have any

00:42:59.000 --> 00:43:01.000
[Guest]: grand vision of his own, was at the time seen

00:43:01.000 --> 00:43:03.000
[Guest]: as quite a conciliatory

00:43:03.000 --> 00:43:05.000
[Guest]: figure, was able to negotiate

00:43:05.000 --> 00:43:07.000
[Guest]: and had been a fairly decent

00:43:07.000 --> 00:43:09.000
[Guest]: foreign minister in terms of his approach

00:43:09.000 --> 00:43:11.000
[Guest]: to other heads of states.

00:43:11.000 --> 00:43:13.000
[Guest]: But, you know, not cut out to be a president.

00:43:13.000 --> 00:43:15.000
[Guest]: So he takes on the approach

00:43:15.000 --> 00:43:17.000
[Guest]: of, Chavez was loved.

00:43:17.000 --> 00:43:19.000
[Guest]: I was designated to be his successor.

00:43:19.000 --> 00:43:21.000
[Guest]: Therefore, I shall not tweak any of

00:43:21.000 --> 00:43:23.000
[Guest]: his policies.

00:43:23.000 --> 00:43:25.000
[Guest]: And he stands firm,

00:43:25.000 --> 00:43:27.000
[Guest]: you know, backing these increasingly

00:43:27.000 --> 00:43:29.000
[Guest]: ludicrous and destructive

00:43:29.000 --> 00:43:31.000
[Guest]: policies as Venezuela's economy

00:43:31.000 --> 00:43:33.000
[Guest]: utterly unravels.

00:43:33.000 --> 00:43:35.000
[Guest]: And there starts to be increasing pressure for, look,

00:43:35.000 --> 00:43:37.000
[Guest]: you have to devalue, you have to let private

00:43:37.000 --> 00:43:39.000
[Guest]: investment in, you have to start to lift the

00:43:39.000 --> 00:43:41.000
[Guest]: currency controls, you have to

00:43:41.000 --> 00:43:43.000
[Guest]: increase gasoline prices, and Venezuela

00:43:43.000 --> 00:43:45.000
[Guest]: has the cheapest gasoline prices in the world.

00:43:45.000 --> 00:43:47.000
[Guest]: It's essentially free. Another one of the

00:43:47.000 --> 00:43:49.000
[Guest]: wild distortions of this magical

00:43:49.000 --> 00:43:51.000
[Guest]: realist place. But Maduro does

00:43:51.000 --> 00:43:53.000
[Guest]: not do any of that. So progressively

00:43:53.000 --> 00:43:55.000
[Guest]: the situation just spirals entirely

00:43:55.000 --> 00:43:57.000
[Guest]: out of control. When I arrived

00:43:57.000 --> 00:43:59.000
[Guest]: in 2014,

00:43:59.000 --> 00:44:01.000
[Guest]: there were odd shortages, right?

00:44:01.000 --> 00:44:03.000
[Guest]: I'd go to the supermarket and I'd ask

00:44:03.000 --> 00:44:05.000
[Guest]: for coffee and they'd say, oh no, we don't have any.

00:44:05.000 --> 00:44:07.000
[Guest]: And I remember one security guard said, well, come back

00:44:07.000 --> 00:44:09.000
[Guest]: tomorrow, I think we're going to get a shipment tomorrow, you know,

00:44:09.000 --> 00:44:11.000
[Guest]: in kind of a conspiratorial whisper.

00:44:11.000 --> 00:44:13.000
[Guest]: Okay, so I came back the next day and I got my coffee, right?

00:44:13.000 --> 00:44:15.000
[Guest]: But over time, it became

00:44:15.000 --> 00:44:17.000
[Guest]: far more critical.

00:44:17.000 --> 00:44:19.000
[Guest]: And that's when you really started having people

00:44:19.000 --> 00:44:21.000
[Guest]: getting malnourished, people dying

00:44:21.000 --> 00:44:23.000
[Guest]: of preventable diseases,

00:44:23.000 --> 00:44:25.000
[Guest]: you know, like diphtheria returned

00:44:25.000 --> 00:44:27.000
[Guest]: because there was a shortage of vaccines

00:44:27.000 --> 00:44:29.000
[Guest]: and the whole health system disintegrated.

00:44:29.000 --> 00:44:31.000
[Guest]: Cancer patients

00:44:31.000 --> 00:44:33.000
[Guest]: couldn't find their oncological medicine anymore.

00:44:33.000 --> 00:44:35.000
[Guest]: Even people who

00:44:35.000 --> 00:44:37.000
[Guest]: had successfully overcome things, like

00:44:37.000 --> 00:44:39.000
[Guest]: gotten a transplant for a failed organ

00:44:39.000 --> 00:44:41.000
[Guest]: and were living and happy

00:44:41.000 --> 00:44:43.000
[Guest]: suddenly couldn't find the medicine

00:44:43.000 --> 00:44:45.000
[Guest]: they needed to help stop their organ from being rejected.

00:44:45.000 --> 00:44:47.000
[Guest]: So just the

00:44:47.000 --> 00:44:49.000
[Guest]: humanitarian crisis balloons.

00:44:49.000 --> 00:44:51.000
[Guest]: And Maduro and his acolytes

00:44:51.000 --> 00:44:53.000
[Guest]: just dig in, essentially

00:44:53.000 --> 00:44:55.000
[Guest]: ignore reality.

00:44:55.000 --> 00:44:57.000
[Guest]: They both ignore it and blame it

00:44:57.000 --> 00:44:59.000
[Guest]: on the opposition without ever

00:44:59.000 --> 00:45:01.000
[Guest]: kind of acknowledging how dramatic

00:45:01.000 --> 00:45:03.000
[Guest]: it's gotten.

00:45:03.000 --> 00:45:05.000
[Guest]: They undeniably live in a bubble.

00:45:05.000 --> 00:45:07.000
[Guest]: They limit their outside interaction

00:45:07.000 --> 00:45:09.000
[Guest]: with the people. Everything is very choreographed

00:45:09.000 --> 00:45:11.000
[Guest]: and stage managed.

00:45:11.000 --> 00:45:13.000
[Guest]: And, you know, it's gotten to a point

00:45:13.000 --> 00:45:15.000
[Guest]: of no return where it's so difficult

00:45:15.000 --> 00:45:17.000
[Guest]: to reform the economy now unless you have a major bailout.

00:45:17.000 --> 00:45:19.000
[Guest]: Because anything you would

00:45:19.000 --> 00:45:21.000
[Guest]: touch could be dynamite, right?

00:45:21.000 --> 00:45:23.000
[Guest]: If you lift currency controls

00:45:23.000 --> 00:45:25.000
[Guest]: now or something, it could just completely destabilize

00:45:25.000 --> 00:45:27.000
[Guest]: and wreck the country in the short term.

00:45:27.000 --> 00:45:29.000
[Guest]: And they don't have the economic know-how

00:45:29.000 --> 00:45:31.000
[Guest]: or the wherewithal to do that.

00:45:31.000 --> 00:45:33.000
[Guest]: So he's just dug himself into a complete hole.

00:45:33.000 --> 00:45:35.000
[Amit Varma]: And I believe

00:45:35.000 --> 00:45:37.000
[Amit Varma]: there's a refugee crisis out of Venezuela

00:45:37.000 --> 00:45:39.000
[Amit Varma]: which people have compared to Syria

00:45:39.000 --> 00:45:41.000
[Amit Varma]: and said it's actually worse and anyone

00:45:41.000 --> 00:45:43.000
[Amit Varma]: who can get out somehow, anyhow, is getting

00:45:43.000 --> 00:45:45.000
[Amit Varma]: out because it's just not feasible anymore.

00:45:45.000 --> 00:45:47.000
[Guest]: Oh yes. I mean, the initial

00:45:47.000 --> 00:45:49.000
[Guest]: wave happened during the Chavez era

00:45:49.000 --> 00:45:51.000
[Guest]: when wealthy people, especially businessmen

00:45:51.000 --> 00:45:53.000
[Guest]: said, this is not smelling right,

00:45:53.000 --> 00:45:55.000
[Guest]: I'm getting out. But they left, you know,

00:45:55.000 --> 00:45:57.000
[Guest]: they took a plane, they had their money,

00:45:57.000 --> 00:45:59.000
[Guest]: they settled in Miami and Madrid

00:45:59.000 --> 00:46:01.000
[Guest]: and continued being doctors or engineers.

00:46:01.000 --> 00:46:03.000
[Guest]: It was sad, of course, but their life went on

00:46:03.000 --> 00:46:05.000
[Guest]: and they're doing well.

00:46:05.000 --> 00:46:07.000
[Guest]: But what happened under the Maduro government

00:46:07.000 --> 00:46:09.000
[Guest]: is the poor people suffered the worst.

00:46:09.000 --> 00:46:11.000
[Guest]: The poor and the middle class that got

00:46:11.000 --> 00:46:13.000
[Guest]: thrown into poverty because of hyperinflation

00:46:13.000 --> 00:46:15.000
[Guest]: and the general economic situation.

00:46:15.000 --> 00:46:17.000
[Guest]: And initially a lot of them left

00:46:17.000 --> 00:46:19.000
[Guest]: by bus or short-haul flight

00:46:19.000 --> 00:46:21.000
[Guest]: to the rest of Latin America.

00:46:21.000 --> 00:46:23.000
[Guest]: But increasingly what we're seeing is dirt poor people

00:46:23.000 --> 00:46:25.000
[Guest]: just walking across

00:46:25.000 --> 00:46:27.000
[Guest]: Latin America to as far as they can,

00:46:27.000 --> 00:46:29.000
[Amit Varma]: as far as their money will carry them.

00:46:29.000 --> 00:46:31.000
[Amit Varma]: And how does the international community

00:46:31.000 --> 00:46:33.000
[Amit Varma]: deal with this? Because

00:46:33.000 --> 00:46:35.000
[Amit Varma]: there's also a wariness over time

00:46:35.000 --> 00:46:37.000
[Amit Varma]: of interfering with other countries' private

00:46:37.000 --> 00:46:39.000
[Amit Varma]: matters. And this is also

00:46:39.000 --> 00:46:41.000
[Amit Varma]: a complicated area for someone

00:46:41.000 --> 00:46:43.000
[Amit Varma]: like the US to sort of

00:46:43.000 --> 00:46:45.000
[Amit Varma]: do something about because there is also

00:46:45.000 --> 00:46:47.000
[Amit Varma]: this narrative about how

00:46:47.000 --> 00:46:49.000
[Amit Varma]: Chavez and Maduro after him are these

00:46:49.000 --> 00:46:51.000
[Amit Varma]: great saviors of communism

00:46:51.000 --> 00:46:53.000
[Unknown]: and these neoliberals are

00:46:53.000 --> 00:46:55.000
[Unknown]: constantly interfering and they

00:46:55.000 --> 00:46:57.000
[Unknown]: are to blame. A narrative

00:46:57.000 --> 00:46:59.000
[Amit Varma]: pushed to a large extent by Chavez himself and

00:46:59.000 --> 00:47:01.000
[Amit Varma]: quite masterfully pushed but obviously

00:47:01.000 --> 00:47:03.000
[Amit Varma]: utterly untrue. So how does

00:47:03.000 --> 00:47:05.000
[Amit Varma]: the international community then deal

00:47:05.000 --> 00:47:07.000
[Amit Varma]: with that? They have to be wary of responding

00:47:07.000 --> 00:47:09.000
[Amit Varma]: but at the same time when there is such a massive

00:47:09.000 --> 00:47:11.000
[Amit Varma]: humanitarian crisis going on

00:47:11.000 --> 00:47:13.000
[Amit Varma]: it's hard to also say we'll

00:47:13.000 --> 00:47:15.000
[Guest]: do nothing. Yes, I think that was a big

00:47:15.000 --> 00:47:17.000
[Guest]: quandary especially for Latin America where sensitivities

00:47:17.000 --> 00:47:19.000
[Guest]: to US involvement are so high.

00:47:19.000 --> 00:47:21.000
[Guest]: And for most of Chavez's

00:47:21.000 --> 00:47:23.000
[Guest]: governance, much of

00:47:23.000 --> 00:47:25.000
[Guest]: the rest of South America was also

00:47:25.000 --> 00:47:27.000
[Guest]: ruled by the left wing. It was very cozy with

00:47:27.000 --> 00:47:29.000
[Guest]: Chavez and in some instances

00:47:29.000 --> 00:47:31.000
[Guest]: possibly benefited from his oil largesse

00:47:31.000 --> 00:47:33.000
[Guest]: or just private funds for campaigns.

00:47:33.000 --> 00:47:35.000
[Guest]: So there's very muted criticism of him.

00:47:35.000 --> 00:47:37.000
[Guest]: Over time that

00:47:37.000 --> 00:47:39.000
[Guest]: pink tide, as it was called, has

00:47:39.000 --> 00:47:41.000
[Guest]: ebbed over Latin America with the commodities price

00:47:41.000 --> 00:47:43.000
[Guest]: crash. So now actually you have a

00:47:43.000 --> 00:47:45.000
[Guest]: string of right wing governments.

00:47:45.000 --> 00:47:47.000
[Guest]: Still there was wariness about confronting him

00:47:47.000 --> 00:47:49.000
[Guest]: directly but the fact that

00:47:49.000 --> 00:47:51.000
[Guest]: so many migrants and refugees were spilling into

00:47:51.000 --> 00:47:53.000
[Guest]: Colombia, Ecuador, Peru, Argentina, Chile

00:47:53.000 --> 00:47:55.000
[Guest]: and because the situation

00:47:55.000 --> 00:47:57.000
[Guest]: has deteriorated in terms of human rights

00:47:57.000 --> 00:47:59.000
[Guest]: and democracy so much in Venezuela

00:47:59.000 --> 00:48:01.000
[Guest]: those countries have spoken out.

00:48:01.000 --> 00:48:03.000
[Guest]: But there is still this unease

00:48:03.000 --> 00:48:05.000
[Guest]: with having the US lead

00:48:05.000 --> 00:48:07.000
[Guest]: the charge. And for a long time

00:48:07.000 --> 00:48:09.000
[Guest]: at least under Obama, the US

00:48:09.000 --> 00:48:11.000
[Guest]: administration was pushing Mexico or Brazil

00:48:11.000 --> 00:48:13.000
[Guest]: regional powerhouses

00:48:13.000 --> 00:48:15.000
[Guest]: to lead, to avoid having the US

00:48:15.000 --> 00:48:17.000
[Guest]: be at the forefront because the US

00:48:17.000 --> 00:48:19.000
[Guest]: has had a track record of supporting

00:48:19.000 --> 00:48:21.000
[Guest]: dictators or even coups in Latin America

00:48:21.000 --> 00:48:23.000
[Guest]: during the Cold War and there's a huge

00:48:23.000 --> 00:48:25.000
[Guest]: amount of resentment against the United States

00:48:25.000 --> 00:48:27.000
[Guest]: for that and that helps explain

00:48:27.000 --> 00:48:29.000
[Guest]: the rise of people like Chavez.

00:48:29.000 --> 00:48:31.000
[Guest]: I think now

00:48:31.000 --> 00:48:33.000
[Guest]: because Latin America is dominated

00:48:33.000 --> 00:48:35.000
[Guest]: by the right and because

00:48:35.000 --> 00:48:37.000
[Guest]: there's so much sense of such urgency

00:48:37.000 --> 00:48:39.000
[Amit Varma]: they're all behind Trump.

00:48:39.000 --> 00:48:41.000
[Amit Varma]: And a lot of the resentment

00:48:41.000 --> 00:48:43.000
[Amit Varma]: of course is justified and it takes me back to

00:48:43.000 --> 00:48:45.000
[Amit Varma]: the old story about when

00:48:45.000 --> 00:48:47.000
[Amit Varma]: Chavez comes to power, shortly after he comes to power

00:48:47.000 --> 00:48:49.000
[Amit Varma]: there's a massive earthquake

00:48:49.000 --> 00:48:51.000
[Amit Varma]: where millions get affected

00:48:51.000 --> 00:48:53.000
[Amit Varma]: and the US

00:48:53.000 --> 00:48:55.000
[Amit Varma]: offers to send aid

00:48:55.000 --> 00:48:57.000
[Amit Varma]: Venezuela agrees the aid

00:48:57.000 --> 00:48:59.000
[Amit Varma]: is on its way and then in the middle of the night

00:48:59.000 --> 00:49:01.000
[Amit Varma]: Chavez calls the minister concerned and he says tell them to go back

00:49:01.000 --> 00:49:03.000
[Amit Varma]: and the minister says no, no

00:49:03.000 --> 00:49:05.000
[Amit Varma]: but they're already on their way and we need the help

00:49:05.000 --> 00:49:07.000
[Amit Varma]: we can't do anything about it and he says no, no

00:49:07.000 --> 00:49:09.000
[Amit Varma]: I don't want the Americans here because

00:49:09.000 --> 00:49:11.000
[Amit Varma]: and he gets paranoid about, you know, they'll snoop on us

00:49:11.000 --> 00:49:13.000
[Amit Varma]: and blah, blah, blah and he gets them to go back

00:49:13.000 --> 00:49:15.000
[Amit Varma]: and there is speculation that maybe he spoke to Castro

00:49:15.000 --> 00:49:17.000
[Amit Varma]: overnight and Castro told him to do that

00:49:17.000 --> 00:49:19.000
[Amit Varma]: but whatever the case may be

00:49:19.000 --> 00:49:21.000
[Amit Varma]: but the interesting thing through the Chavez years was

00:49:21.000 --> 00:49:23.000
[Amit Varma]: that although he kept ranting about

00:49:23.000 --> 00:49:25.000
[Amit Varma]: George W. Bush in very funny

00:49:25.000 --> 00:49:27.000
[Amit Varma]: and amusing ways, I'm not going to quote

00:49:27.000 --> 00:49:29.000
[Amit Varma]: any of that but some great quotes

00:49:29.000 --> 00:49:31.000
[Amit Varma]: Google it, although he kept

00:49:31.000 --> 00:49:33.000
[Amit Varma]: ranting about the imperialists

00:49:33.000 --> 00:49:35.000
[Amit Varma]: and the neoliberals and the Americans and so on

00:49:35.000 --> 00:49:37.000
[Amit Varma]: when it came to oil, it was business

00:49:37.000 --> 00:49:39.000
[Amit Varma]: as usual. Venezuela was super

00:49:39.000 --> 00:49:41.000
[Amit Varma]: efficient in supplying oil

00:49:41.000 --> 00:49:43.000
[Amit Varma]: to the US which was the biggest buyer

00:49:43.000 --> 00:49:45.000
[Amit Varma]: and everything there went smoothly

00:49:45.000 --> 00:49:47.000
[Guest]: Yes

00:49:47.000 --> 00:49:49.000
[Guest]: and bilateral relationship had ebbs

00:49:49.000 --> 00:49:51.000
[Guest]: and flows and

00:49:51.000 --> 00:49:53.000
[Guest]: Chavez would kick out the US

00:49:53.000 --> 00:49:55.000
[Guest]: ambassador and vice versa

00:49:55.000 --> 00:49:57.000
[Guest]: and Maduro likewise but the oil kept

00:49:57.000 --> 00:49:59.000
[Guest]: flowing and the US was

00:49:59.000 --> 00:50:01.000
[Guest]: depending on what metric he used

00:50:01.000 --> 00:50:03.000
[Guest]: as the biggest cash paying consumer

00:50:03.000 --> 00:50:05.000
[Guest]: because over time

00:50:05.000 --> 00:50:07.000
[Guest]: Venezuela ended up mortgaging its oil to

00:50:07.000 --> 00:50:09.000
[Guest]: Russia and China to pay back

00:50:09.000 --> 00:50:11.000
[Guest]: loans that they were receiving

00:50:11.000 --> 00:50:13.000
[Guest]: so the US was of crucial importance

00:50:13.000 --> 00:50:15.000
[Guest]: those flows are not changing

00:50:15.000 --> 00:50:17.000
[Guest]: because of sanctions and India

00:50:17.000 --> 00:50:19.000
[Guest]: actually is I think

00:50:19.000 --> 00:50:21.000
[Guest]: becoming or has become the number one

00:50:21.000 --> 00:50:23.000
[Guest]: cash buyer of Venezuelan oil

00:50:23.000 --> 00:50:25.000
[Amit Varma]: Ouch, is this something we should

00:50:25.000 --> 00:50:27.000
[Guest]: feel bad about?

00:50:27.000 --> 00:50:29.000
[Guest]: India's private companies

00:50:29.000 --> 00:50:31.000
[Unknown]: are reporting, right?

00:50:31.000 --> 00:50:33.000
[Guest]: It's a different calculation and

00:50:33.000 --> 00:50:35.000
[Guest]: everything leads to believe that Venezuela

00:50:35.000 --> 00:50:37.000
[Amit Varma]: is offering nice discounts

00:50:37.000 --> 00:50:39.000
[Amit Varma]: Money is fungible

00:50:39.000 --> 00:50:41.000
[Amit Varma]: What's the politics in Venezuela like

00:50:41.000 --> 00:50:43.000
[Amit Varma]: right now?

00:50:43.000 --> 00:50:45.000
[Amit Varma]: One interesting sort of

00:50:45.000 --> 00:50:47.000
[Amit Varma]: turning point in Venezuelan politics

00:50:47.000 --> 00:50:49.000
[Amit Varma]: which is easy to identify and you mentioned

00:50:49.000 --> 00:50:51.000
[Amit Varma]: it in our conversation before the podcast

00:50:51.000 --> 00:50:53.000
[Amit Varma]: was obviously the 2005 elections

00:50:53.000 --> 00:50:55.000
[Amit Varma]: when there was

00:50:55.000 --> 00:50:57.000
[Amit Varma]: this where somebody reported

00:50:57.000 --> 00:50:59.000
[Amit Varma]: that voting is no longer anonymous

00:50:59.000 --> 00:51:01.000
[Amit Varma]: you can find out who's kind of

00:51:01.000 --> 00:51:03.000
[Amit Varma]: voted and because of this

00:51:03.000 --> 00:51:05.000
[Amit Varma]: the entire opposition decided to

00:51:05.000 --> 00:51:07.000
[Amit Varma]: boycott the elections

00:51:07.000 --> 00:51:09.000
[Amit Varma]: and Chavez basically

00:51:09.000 --> 00:51:11.000
[Amit Varma]: swept the assembly seats obviously because

00:51:11.000 --> 00:51:13.000
[Amit Varma]: his party was the only

00:51:13.000 --> 00:51:15.000
[Amit Varma]: contender there. Did that

00:51:15.000 --> 00:51:17.000
[Amit Varma]: have a long term impact? Did the

00:51:17.000 --> 00:51:19.000
[Amit Varma]: opposition recover from that

00:51:19.000 --> 00:51:21.000
[Guest]: and come back strongly and what's the situation

00:51:21.000 --> 00:51:23.000
[Guest]: today?

00:51:23.000 --> 00:51:25.000
[Guest]: The Venezuelan opposition

00:51:25.000 --> 00:51:27.000
[Guest]: has long been elitist, very

00:51:27.000 --> 00:51:29.000
[Guest]: quarrelsome, dominated by a smattering

00:51:29.000 --> 00:51:31.000
[Guest]: of parties that no one's ever heard of abroad but

00:51:31.000 --> 00:51:33.000
[Guest]: who love to fight amongst themselves

00:51:33.000 --> 00:51:35.000
[Guest]: and their boycott of the 2005

00:51:35.000 --> 00:51:37.000
[Guest]: vote essentially annulled

00:51:37.000 --> 00:51:39.000
[Guest]: them from the political scene and gave

00:51:39.000 --> 00:51:41.000
[Guest]: Chavez a complete

00:51:41.000 --> 00:51:43.000
[Guest]: blank check to do whatever he wanted because his

00:51:43.000 --> 00:51:45.000
[Guest]: party controlled the National Assembly

00:51:45.000 --> 00:51:47.000
[Guest]: It also fit into this

00:51:47.000 --> 00:51:49.000
[Guest]: the opposition would repeatedly

00:51:49.000 --> 00:51:51.000
[Guest]: cry wolf before

00:51:51.000 --> 00:51:53.000
[Guest]: when it wasn't necessary, right?

00:51:53.000 --> 00:51:55.000
[Guest]: Chavez was clearly

00:51:55.000 --> 00:51:57.000
[Guest]: problematic for institutions from the start but the

00:51:57.000 --> 00:51:59.000
[Guest]: opposition would be wildly

00:51:59.000 --> 00:52:01.000
[Guest]: exaggerating what was happening and lose credibility

00:52:01.000 --> 00:52:03.000
[Guest]: in the process so by boycotting the elections

00:52:03.000 --> 00:52:05.000
[Guest]: and saying this wasn't a

00:52:05.000 --> 00:52:07.000
[Guest]: democracy and Chavez is the dictator

00:52:07.000 --> 00:52:09.000
[Guest]: when I think a lot of political scientists would say

00:52:09.000 --> 00:52:11.000
[Guest]: he wasn't, he had autocratic tendency but it wasn't

00:52:11.000 --> 00:52:13.000
[Guest]: a dictatorship. They actually facilitated

00:52:13.000 --> 00:52:15.000
[Guest]: his road to creating a

00:52:15.000 --> 00:52:17.000
[Guest]: much more authoritarian government

00:52:17.000 --> 00:52:19.000
[Guest]: Over time the opposition

00:52:19.000 --> 00:52:21.000
[Guest]: has done some soul searching

00:52:21.000 --> 00:52:23.000
[Guest]: and Enrique Capriles who was a

00:52:23.000 --> 00:52:25.000
[Guest]: two time presidential candidate for the opposition

00:52:25.000 --> 00:52:27.000
[Guest]: actually said no

00:52:27.000 --> 00:52:29.000
[Guest]: we cannot demonize Chavistas

00:52:29.000 --> 00:52:31.000
[Guest]: Chavez supporters

00:52:31.000 --> 00:52:33.000
[Guest]: we must talk to them, understand

00:52:33.000 --> 00:52:35.000
[Guest]: why they voted Chavez and show them

00:52:35.000 --> 00:52:37.000
[Guest]: why we're the path forward

00:52:37.000 --> 00:52:39.000
[Guest]: so he actually did crisscross the country

00:52:39.000 --> 00:52:41.000
[Guest]: go into the slums and the poor villages

00:52:41.000 --> 00:52:43.000
[Guest]: and talk to people and won over a lot of them

00:52:43.000 --> 00:52:45.000
[Guest]: not enough to win the election

00:52:45.000 --> 00:52:47.000
[Amit Varma]: again we don't know exactly what happened

00:52:47.000 --> 00:52:49.000
[Guest]: Maybe he won it

00:52:49.000 --> 00:52:51.000
[Guest]: but he changed the narrative

00:52:51.000 --> 00:52:53.000
[Guest]: and kind of shook up what used to be

00:52:53.000 --> 00:52:55.000
[Guest]: kind of a bastion of the

00:52:55.000 --> 00:52:57.000
[Guest]: wealthy Caracas old families

00:52:57.000 --> 00:52:59.000
[Guest]: but in the last few

00:52:59.000 --> 00:53:01.000
[Guest]: years the government crackdown on the opposition

00:53:01.000 --> 00:53:03.000
[Guest]: has been much more ferocious

00:53:03.000 --> 00:53:05.000
[Guest]: so you know you have

00:53:05.000 --> 00:53:07.000
[Guest]: exiled politicians in Washington and Colombia

00:53:07.000 --> 00:53:09.000
[Guest]: in Europe, others who are

00:53:09.000 --> 00:53:11.000
[Guest]: in jail or under house arrest

00:53:11.000 --> 00:53:13.000
[Guest]: or even one who's

00:53:13.000 --> 00:53:15.000
[Guest]: holed up in the Chilean embassy and has been holed up there

00:53:15.000 --> 00:53:17.000
[Guest]: for months if not a year by now

00:53:17.000 --> 00:53:19.000
[Guest]: so they've completely

00:53:19.000 --> 00:53:21.000
[Guest]: chopped up the opposition

00:53:21.000 --> 00:53:23.000
[Guest]: annulled political parties, annulled any

00:53:23.000 --> 00:53:25.000
[Guest]: kind of political movement they tried to create

00:53:25.000 --> 00:53:27.000
[Guest]: to unseat Maduro

00:53:27.000 --> 00:53:29.000
[Guest]: and so it's very hard for them to articulate themselves now

00:53:29.000 --> 00:53:31.000
[Amit Varma]: So where do things stand now

00:53:31.000 --> 00:53:33.000
[Guest]: as of today?

00:53:33.000 --> 00:53:35.000
[Guest]: It's been a whirlwind since January

00:53:35.000 --> 00:53:37.000
[Guest]: so Maduro was sworn in for his second term

00:53:37.000 --> 00:53:39.000
[Guest]: in January after a very

00:53:39.000 --> 00:53:41.000
[Guest]: again a decried election where all the

00:53:41.000 --> 00:53:43.000
[Guest]: Western powers said this was a fraudulent

00:53:43.000 --> 00:53:45.000
[Guest]: vote and everyone kind of

00:53:45.000 --> 00:53:47.000
[Guest]: expected it to be game over

00:53:47.000 --> 00:53:49.000
[Guest]: after that but then

00:53:49.000 --> 00:53:51.000
[Guest]: this new kind of fresh-faced

00:53:51.000 --> 00:53:53.000
[Guest]: opposition leader, Juan Guaido

00:53:53.000 --> 00:53:55.000
[Guest]: who had just become the

00:53:55.000 --> 00:53:57.000
[Guest]: head of the Venezuelan congress

00:53:57.000 --> 00:53:59.000
[Guest]: which is still led by the opposition

00:53:59.000 --> 00:54:01.000
[Guest]: and incidentally he became head of

00:54:01.000 --> 00:54:03.000
[Guest]: the congress because most of the people

00:54:03.000 --> 00:54:05.000
[Guest]: or many of the leaders in his party are either in exile

00:54:05.000 --> 00:54:07.000
[Guest]: in prison or holed up in the

00:54:07.000 --> 00:54:09.000
[Guest]: embassy so he was kind of the last person

00:54:09.000 --> 00:54:11.000
[Guest]: standing and no one expected him

00:54:11.000 --> 00:54:13.000
[Guest]: to become the face of

00:54:13.000 --> 00:54:15.000
[Guest]: the rejuvenated opposition

00:54:15.000 --> 00:54:17.000
[Guest]: so Juan Guaido was 35

00:54:17.000 --> 00:54:19.000
[Guest]: swore himself in

00:54:19.000 --> 00:54:21.000
[Guest]: citing the constitution, his constitutional right

00:54:21.000 --> 00:54:23.000
[Guest]: to do that and declared himself president

00:54:23.000 --> 00:54:25.000
[Guest]: and that just set

00:54:25.000 --> 00:54:27.000
[Guest]: in motion a whole chain of events

00:54:27.000 --> 00:54:29.000
[Guest]: the US supported him, other European

00:54:29.000 --> 00:54:31.000
[Guest]: countries and Latin American countries also recognized

00:54:31.000 --> 00:54:33.000
[Guest]: him, it sparked

00:54:33.000 --> 00:54:35.000
[Guest]: a huge wave of protests

00:54:35.000 --> 00:54:37.000
[Guest]: and we thought the Venezuelan

00:54:37.000 --> 00:54:39.000
[Guest]: people were kind of broken, right? Immigration

00:54:39.000 --> 00:54:41.000
[Guest]: was the way out, everyone has just

00:54:41.000 --> 00:54:43.000
[Guest]: lost hope that anything could ever change and

00:54:43.000 --> 00:54:45.000
[Guest]: almost overnight it seems that people took to the street

00:54:45.000 --> 00:54:47.000
[Guest]: with renewed hope

00:54:47.000 --> 00:54:49.000
[Guest]: there was hope

00:54:49.000 --> 00:54:51.000
[Guest]: in the US and amongst the

00:54:51.000 --> 00:54:53.000
[Guest]: opposition that the military would

00:54:53.000 --> 00:54:55.000
[Guest]: immediately defect and support Guaido

00:54:55.000 --> 00:54:57.000
[Guest]: that did not happen

00:54:57.000 --> 00:54:59.000
[Guest]: the military in Venezuela is essentially an

00:54:59.000 --> 00:55:01.000
[Guest]: extension of the government, it has control

00:55:01.000 --> 00:55:03.000
[Guest]: over whatever lucrative business is left

00:55:03.000 --> 00:55:05.000
[Guest]: in the country. Plan B was

00:55:05.000 --> 00:55:07.000
[Guest]: to try to force in humanitarian aid

00:55:07.000 --> 00:55:09.000
[Guest]: so we had a standoff at the

00:55:09.000 --> 00:55:11.000
[Guest]: Venezuelan border

00:55:11.000 --> 00:55:13.000
[Guest]: a few days ago

00:55:13.000 --> 00:55:15.000
[Guest]: where the

00:55:15.000 --> 00:55:17.000
[Guest]: opposition tried to drive in these trucks

00:55:17.000 --> 00:55:19.000
[Guest]: full with food and

00:55:19.000 --> 00:55:21.000
[Guest]: the Venezuelan soldiers blocked them and there were

00:55:21.000 --> 00:55:23.000
[Guest]: confrontations, tear gas and Molotov cocktails

00:55:23.000 --> 00:55:25.000
[Guest]: etc, but it failed

00:55:25.000 --> 00:55:27.000
[Guest]: there was a number of defections, an

00:55:27.000 --> 00:55:29.000
[Guest]: increasing number of defections from rank

00:55:29.000 --> 00:55:31.000
[Guest]: and file soldiers, I think we're at about over 500

00:55:31.000 --> 00:55:33.000
[Guest]: now, which is interesting and it's increasing

00:55:33.000 --> 00:55:35.000
[Guest]: every day, it's not a groundswell

00:55:35.000 --> 00:55:37.000
[Guest]: and we're not talking about the big fish, but it's

00:55:37.000 --> 00:55:39.000
[Guest]: something to monitor.

00:55:39.000 --> 00:55:41.000
[Guest]: Guaido left Venezuela

00:55:41.000 --> 00:55:43.000
[Guest]: to see the aid through from Colombia

00:55:43.000 --> 00:55:45.000
[Guest]: and is now in Brazil, meeting

00:55:45.000 --> 00:55:47.000
[Guest]: the president there. He's vowed

00:55:47.000 --> 00:55:49.000
[Guest]: to come back to Venezuela

00:55:49.000 --> 00:55:51.000
[Guest]: but Maduro has said

00:55:51.000 --> 00:55:53.000
[Guest]: there was a travel ban on you, if you return

00:55:53.000 --> 00:55:55.000
[Guest]: you shall be detained. So

00:55:55.000 --> 00:55:57.000
[Guest]: there's a big question there and possibly

00:55:57.000 --> 00:55:59.000
[Amit Varma]: a looming confrontation.

00:55:59.000 --> 00:56:01.000
[Amit Varma]: It seems like the political scientist

00:56:01.000 --> 00:56:03.000
[Amit Varma]: A.O. Hirschman once said that if you're

00:56:03.000 --> 00:56:05.000
[Amit Varma]: dissatisfied with the government you have three options

00:56:05.000 --> 00:56:07.000
[Amit Varma]: which are you comply, you complain

00:56:07.000 --> 00:56:09.000
[Amit Varma]: or you leave. And when I first

00:56:09.000 --> 00:56:11.000
[Amit Varma]: heard that quote, I thought okay, no one's going to leave, who can

00:56:11.000 --> 00:56:13.000
[Amit Varma]: leave, you know, but now what's happening is that

00:56:13.000 --> 00:56:15.000
[Amit Varma]: there are people who have simply no option

00:56:15.000 --> 00:56:17.000
[Amit Varma]: they cannot comply because they do not

00:56:17.000 --> 00:56:19.000
[Amit Varma]: have food and there's no point complaining

00:56:19.000 --> 00:56:21.000
[Amit Varma]: so they're leaving and

00:56:21.000 --> 00:56:23.000
[Amit Varma]: it's just, and this is again like you

00:56:23.000 --> 00:56:25.000
[Amit Varma]: said, it's the poorest of the poor, so it's

00:56:25.000 --> 00:56:27.000
[Amit Varma]: a kind of a

00:56:27.000 --> 00:56:29.000
[Amit Varma]: ludicrous situation

00:56:29.000 --> 00:56:31.000
[Amit Varma]: going forward for Venezuela

00:56:31.000 --> 00:56:33.000
[Amit Varma]: then, given the state of the politics

00:56:33.000 --> 00:56:35.000
[Amit Varma]: and the state of the economy, what's a

00:56:35.000 --> 00:56:37.000
[Amit Varma]: best case scenario and what's a worst case

00:56:37.000 --> 00:56:39.000
[Guest]: scenario in your view?

00:56:39.000 --> 00:56:41.000
[Guest]: It's

00:56:41.000 --> 00:56:43.000
[Guest]: kind of difficult for me to pine as a journalist

00:56:43.000 --> 00:56:45.000
[Guest]: but I would say that

00:56:45.000 --> 00:56:47.000
[Guest]: because a majority of people

00:56:47.000 --> 00:56:49.000
[Guest]: seem to want elections and there are

00:56:49.000 --> 00:56:51.000
[Guest]: significant doubts about the previous election

00:56:51.000 --> 00:56:53.000
[Guest]: the ideal scenario

00:56:53.000 --> 00:56:55.000
[Guest]: for many people would probably

00:56:55.000 --> 00:56:57.000
[Guest]: be to hold fair

00:56:57.000 --> 00:56:59.000
[Guest]: and just elections where the people can actually

00:56:59.000 --> 00:57:01.000
[Guest]: express their desire

00:57:01.000 --> 00:57:03.000
[Guest]: and that is highly

00:57:03.000 --> 00:57:05.000
[Guest]: unlikely to happen

00:57:05.000 --> 00:57:07.000
[Guest]: there are many worst case scenarios

00:57:07.000 --> 00:57:09.000
[Guest]: it's hard to say which is worst

00:57:09.000 --> 00:57:11.000
[Guest]: Venezuela is constantly defied to expectations

00:57:11.000 --> 00:57:13.000
[Guest]: of how bad it can get and

00:57:13.000 --> 00:57:15.000
[Guest]: unfortunately I have no

00:57:15.000 --> 00:57:17.000
[Guest]: I know

00:57:17.000 --> 00:57:19.000
[Guest]: it can get worse, I think what's most

00:57:19.000 --> 00:57:21.000
[Guest]: worried me is how lawless it can become

00:57:21.000 --> 00:57:23.000
[Guest]: in many ways of course the government

00:57:23.000 --> 00:57:25.000
[Guest]: is autocratic but it also doesn't

00:57:25.000 --> 00:57:27.000
[Guest]: have control over many of the factions

00:57:27.000 --> 00:57:29.000
[Guest]: that rule the country, the gangs

00:57:29.000 --> 00:57:31.000
[Guest]: the crime rings

00:57:31.000 --> 00:57:33.000
[Guest]: and then just the kind of isolated

00:57:33.000 --> 00:57:35.000
[Guest]: rural areas where there's no state

00:57:35.000 --> 00:57:37.000
[Guest]: there's no infrastructure

00:57:37.000 --> 00:57:39.000
[Guest]: there are no services and

00:57:39.000 --> 00:57:41.000
[Guest]: nothing works, nothing works

00:57:41.000 --> 00:57:43.000
[Guest]: you can't make a phone call, you can't buy food

00:57:43.000 --> 00:57:45.000
[Guest]: you can't transfer money, you can't get on the internet

00:57:45.000 --> 00:57:47.000
[Guest]: you can't wash your clothes

00:57:47.000 --> 00:57:49.000
[Guest]: there's no water, you can't turn on the light switch

00:57:49.000 --> 00:57:51.000
[Guest]: I mean we're just talking about a complete

00:57:51.000 --> 00:57:53.000
[Guest]: collapse in every single way

00:57:53.000 --> 00:57:55.000
[Amit Varma]: Sounds like Afghanistan

00:57:55.000 --> 00:57:57.000
[Amit Varma]: at its worst with the exception that this is

00:57:57.000 --> 00:57:59.000
[Amit Varma]: a country that has enough oil to

00:57:59.000 --> 00:58:01.000
[Amit Varma]: last it for more than 300 years

00:58:01.000 --> 00:58:03.000
[Amit Varma]: this country should be insanely rich

00:58:03.000 --> 00:58:05.000
[Guest]: Absolutely

00:58:05.000 --> 00:58:07.000
[Guest]: and it's also a tropical country

00:58:07.000 --> 00:58:09.000
[Guest]: the vegetation is somewhat similar to

00:58:09.000 --> 00:58:11.000
[Guest]: to Mumbai actually

00:58:11.000 --> 00:58:13.000
[Guest]: so it's so incongruent to see

00:58:13.000 --> 00:58:15.000
[Guest]: people who are famished who show you their

00:58:15.000 --> 00:58:17.000
[Guest]: ID cards and you can't recognize them because they were

00:58:17.000 --> 00:58:19.000
[Guest]: so plump four years ago and now

00:58:19.000 --> 00:58:21.000
[Guest]: are just a shadow of themselves

00:58:21.000 --> 00:58:23.000
[Guest]: and they're climbing up trees trying to get mangoes

00:58:23.000 --> 00:58:25.000
[Guest]: because this is a bountiful country

00:58:25.000 --> 00:58:27.000
[Guest]: and thank God because otherwise people would have

00:58:27.000 --> 00:58:29.000
[Guest]: been in even more dire

00:58:29.000 --> 00:58:31.000
[Guest]: straits and I'm not excusing

00:58:31.000 --> 00:58:33.000
[Guest]: hunger in deserts

00:58:33.000 --> 00:58:35.000
[Guest]: or in Siberia or what have you but it's

00:58:35.000 --> 00:58:37.000
[Guest]: just so shocking to see that in a

00:58:37.000 --> 00:58:39.000
[Guest]: country that is actually very fertile

00:58:39.000 --> 00:58:41.000
[Guest]: and where bananas and mangoes and coconuts

00:58:41.000 --> 00:58:43.000
[Guest]: are growing wildly on every corner

00:58:43.000 --> 00:58:45.000
[Amit Varma]: Blessed by nature and cursed by humans

00:58:45.000 --> 00:58:47.000
[Amit Varma]: Yes

00:58:47.000 --> 00:58:49.000
[Amit Varma]: So this has been a very illuminating episode

00:58:49.000 --> 00:58:51.000
[Amit Varma]: but I'm going to end it by asking

00:58:51.000 --> 00:58:53.000
[Amit Varma]: a question that kind of takes a step back

00:58:53.000 --> 00:58:55.000
[Amit Varma]: I mean

00:58:55.000 --> 00:58:57.000
[Amit Varma]: in the current times that we live in there

00:58:57.000 --> 00:58:59.000
[Amit Varma]: obviously is an upsurge of

00:58:59.000 --> 00:59:01.000
[Amit Varma]: populism all across the world in fact

00:59:01.000 --> 00:59:03.000
[Amit Varma]: you know just reading the biographies

00:59:03.000 --> 00:59:05.000
[Amit Varma]: of Chavez it struck me

00:59:05.000 --> 00:59:07.000
[Amit Varma]: in how many ways he's common

00:59:07.000 --> 00:59:09.000
[Amit Varma]: to the likes of Modi, Erdogan, Orban

00:59:09.000 --> 00:59:11.000
[Amit Varma]: I mean there are so many commonalities

00:59:11.000 --> 00:59:13.000
[Amit Varma]: and one phrase I came across again and again

00:59:13.000 --> 00:59:15.000
[Unknown]: which I thought was a lovely phrase was Chavismo

00:59:15.000 --> 00:59:17.000
[Amit Varma]: So tell me a little bit about

00:59:17.000 --> 00:59:19.000
[Amit Varma]: Chavismo and tell me a little bit about

00:59:19.000 --> 00:59:21.000
[Amit Varma]: Chavismo not just in a Venezuelan

00:59:21.000 --> 00:59:23.000
[Amit Varma]: context but Chavismo

00:59:23.000 --> 00:59:25.000
[Amit Varma]: in a global context and do you think

00:59:25.000 --> 00:59:27.000
[Amit Varma]: you know why do you think it's

00:59:27.000 --> 00:59:29.000
[Amit Varma]: there and what can be

00:59:29.000 --> 00:59:31.000
[Amit Varma]: done about it by people who are concerned

00:59:31.000 --> 00:59:33.000
[Guest]: about it?

00:59:33.000 --> 00:59:35.000
[Guest]: To be fair I think Chavismo at its

00:59:35.000 --> 00:59:37.000
[Guest]: best and in its heart was

00:59:37.000 --> 00:59:39.000
[Guest]: a dream of a people

00:59:39.000 --> 00:59:41.000
[Guest]: to have justice, to reap

00:59:41.000 --> 00:59:43.000
[Guest]: the rewards of this

00:59:43.000 --> 00:59:45.000
[Guest]: bountiful country and to

00:59:45.000 --> 00:59:47.000
[Amit Varma]: right past wrongs

00:59:47.000 --> 00:59:49.000
[Guest]: But that's a rhetorical thing

00:59:49.000 --> 00:59:51.000
[Guest]: Yes but people really

00:59:51.000 --> 00:59:53.000
[Guest]: fervently believe that and as

00:59:53.000 --> 00:59:55.000
[Guest]: I mentioned they kind of believe it

00:59:55.000 --> 00:59:57.000
[Guest]: as a religion. So I remember speaking to a

00:59:57.000 --> 00:59:59.000
[Guest]: social worker who says how can I

00:59:59.000 --> 01:00:01.000
[Guest]: un-teach my children this is what I believe

01:00:01.000 --> 01:00:03.000
[Guest]: it's like a religion for me

01:00:03.000 --> 01:00:05.000
[Guest]: it's so deeply ingrained

01:00:05.000 --> 01:00:07.000
[Guest]: that it's almost like severing part of

01:00:07.000 --> 01:00:09.000
[Guest]: yourself to stop believing or to

01:00:09.000 --> 01:00:11.000
[Guest]: finally face the writing on the wall

01:00:13.000 --> 01:00:15.000
[Guest]: What it turned out to be

01:00:15.000 --> 01:00:17.000
[Guest]: is an obscene

01:00:17.000 --> 01:00:19.000
[Guest]: level of patronage, cronyism

01:00:19.000 --> 01:00:21.000
[Guest]: and perhaps

01:00:21.000 --> 01:00:23.000
[Guest]: a massive money laundering

01:00:23.000 --> 01:00:25.000
[Amit Varma]: and drug trading operation

01:00:25.000 --> 01:00:27.000
[Amit Varma]: Like all religions are false religions

01:00:27.000 --> 01:00:29.000
[Amit Varma]: I think yes

01:00:29.000 --> 01:00:31.000
[Amit Varma]: Sorry that's my view

01:00:31.000 --> 01:00:33.000
[Guest]: I mean it strayed so dramatically

01:00:33.000 --> 01:00:35.000
[Guest]: from the rhetoric of Chavez in the

01:00:35.000 --> 01:00:37.000
[Guest]: early days that it's

01:00:37.000 --> 01:00:39.000
[Guest]: absolutely shocking

01:00:39.000 --> 01:00:41.000
[Guest]: I've wrestled for a long time with what the global

01:00:41.000 --> 01:00:43.000
[Guest]: implications are for this because

01:00:43.000 --> 01:00:45.000
[Guest]: Venezuela is such a one-off it seems

01:00:45.000 --> 01:00:47.000
[Guest]: in many ways of course it's a cautionary tale

01:00:47.000 --> 01:00:49.000
[Guest]: in terms of squandering

01:00:49.000 --> 01:00:51.000
[Guest]: oil wealth or following

01:00:51.000 --> 01:00:53.000
[Guest]: for populist sellers

01:00:53.000 --> 01:00:55.000
[Guest]: of dreams but it's also

01:00:55.000 --> 01:00:57.000
[Guest]: pushed things to such an

01:00:57.000 --> 01:00:59.000
[Guest]: extreme that it's sometimes

01:00:59.000 --> 01:01:01.000
[Guest]: hard to extrapolate

01:01:01.000 --> 01:01:03.000
[Guest]: but yes I think certain

01:01:03.000 --> 01:01:05.000
[Guest]: certain themes

01:01:05.000 --> 01:01:07.000
[Guest]: certain boring but fundamental themes

01:01:07.000 --> 01:01:09.000
[Guest]: like fiscal responsibility and

01:01:09.000 --> 01:01:11.000
[Guest]: the importance of institutions come to mind

01:01:11.000 --> 01:01:13.000
[Guest]: as trite as that

01:01:13.000 --> 01:01:15.000
[Guest]: is you never realize their

01:01:15.000 --> 01:01:17.000
[Guest]: value more than when all of that is crumbling

